{"title_page": "Interstate 291 (Massachusetts)", "text_new": "{{short description|Highway in Massachusetts}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|route=291\n|alternate_name=Springfield Expressway\n|type=I\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|frame-lat=42.135|frame-long=-72.573|zoom=12|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 291 (Massachusetts)}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=I-291 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=5.44\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"fhwa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/reports/routefinder/table2.htm|title=Route Log - Auxiliary Routes of the Eisenhower National System of Interstate and Defense Highways - Table 2|publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]]|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>\n|established=1971<ref name=\"completion\">{{cite web| publisher= AA Roads Interstate Guide| url= http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-291_ma.html#east_end |title= Interstate-Guide: Interstate 291 Massachusetts| accessdate= January 1, 2014}}\n* {{cite news|title=Junkyards, old factories line 291|last=Briere|first=Glen A.|date=September 12, 1971|page=24|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n|spur_type=I\n|spur_of=91\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MA|I|91}} in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|20|MA|20A|nolink2=y}} in Springfield\n*{{jct|state=MA|I|90|MATP}} in Chicopee\n}}\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b=Burnett Road in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]]\n|counties=[[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]]\n|previous_type=I\n|previous_route=290\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=295\n}}\n[[Image:Interstate 291 eastbound, Springfield MA.jpg|thumb|right|250px|<center>Eastbound</center>]]\n'''Interstate 291''' (abbreviated '''I-291'''), also known as the '''Springfield Expressway''',<ref name=\"bostonroads\">[http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/I-291_MA/ Springfield Expressway (I-291)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> is a {{convert|5.44|mi|km|adj=on}} connector highway in [[Massachusetts]] that links [[Interstate 91]] in downtown [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]] with [[Interstate 90 in Massachusetts|Interstate 90]] (the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]) in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]]. I-291 is roughly a northeast/southwest highway. It merges with I-91 at its southwestern terminus, via a flyover. The road meets the Mass Pike at its northeastern terminus. Getting onto the Pike from I-291 is straightforward, but getting from the Pike to I-291 requires a left turn at an at-grade traffic signal. I-291 travels directly through highly populated areas of Springfield, and passes under several overpasses. From its southwestern terminus to exit 5A, Interstate 291 is [[Concurrency (road)|concurrent]] with [[U.S. Route 20]].\n\nI-291 is only {{convert|22.4|mi|km}} from [[Interstate 291 (Connecticut)|Interstate 291]] in [[Connecticut]], and there are no intervening Interstate Highway interchanges between them. It can be easy for travelers to become confused between the two highways.{{fact|date=January 2009}}\n\n==Route description==\nInterstate 291 begins as a spur of Interstate 91 at Exit 8 in Springfield, concurrent with U.S. 20, which merges from the north. The two entry ramps from I-91 merge with each other after Exits 2A and 2B, where a sign for the beginning of I-291 east is posted. I-291 and U.S. 20 run eastbound concurrently until Exit 5A (U.S. 20 joins westbound at Exit 5), where U.S. 20 east leaves the highway for a junction with [[Massachusetts Route 20A|Route 20A]]. I-291 continues east into Chicopee, where it intersects the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] ([[Interstate 90]]).  I-291 ends at an odd intersection at a stoplight on Burnett Road, but I-291 east traffic can exit uninterrupted by way of a ramp to the Mass Pike. However, drivers coming from the Mass Pike must deal with this traffic light, as a left turn across the intersection is required to get on I-291 west.\n\nThe westbound interchange with I-91 is unusual in that the ramps for Exit 1A-B split before the ramps for Exits 2A-B do.  Traffic bound for Exit 2A (Chestnut Street) must first take the ramp for Exit 1A (I-91 South), and traffic bound for Exit 2B (Dwight St.) must first take the ramp for Exit 1B (I-91 North).\n\nTraffic bound for U.S. 20 West from I-291 takes Exit 1B. U.S. 20 does not actually join with I-91, but rather this exit splits, left for the on-ramp to I-91 North, the right to continue on the U.S. 20 access ramp.\n\n==History==\nI-291 was originally conceived in 1953, prior to the creation of the Interstate Highway System, as the Springfield Expressway, which would bypass [[U.S. Route 20 in Massachusetts|US 20]] and connect to the [[U.S. Route 5 in Massachusetts|US 5 expressway]] (now I-91) and the proposed [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]. I-291 follows the original planned alignment of the expressway, except for the stretch between exit 4 (St. James Avenue) and exit 5 (US 20/MA 20A/Page Boulevard). The original planned alignment had the route turn in almost a perfect 90 degree angle onto Roosevelt Avenue, but industrial development (including the relocation of [[Smith & Wesson]]'s corporate headquarters) had the highway turn more gently. The first section of the expressway that was built was the bridge over the [[Chicopee River]].<ref>{{cite web| publisher= Boston Roads |url= http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/I-291_MA/ |title= Springfield Expressway (I-291)| accessdate= January 1, 2014}}</ref> The first section of the expressway that opened was from US 20/MA 20A to I-90 (Mass. Turnpike) in 1957; work on the freeway started up again in 1967 and the entire highway was completed in 1971.<ref name=\"completion\"/> The construction delay was due to I-91 having priority through western Massachusetts.\n\n==Exit list==\nAll interchanges were to be renumbered to mileage-based numbers under a project scheduled to start in 2016.<ref name=\"Exit Numbers\">{{cite web|author=Commonwealth of Massachusetts|year=2015|title=COMMBUYS - Bid Solicitation FAP# HSIP-002S(874) Exit Signage Conversion to Milepost-Based Numbering System along Various Interstates, Routes and the Lowell Connector |url=https://www.commbuys.com/bso/external/bidDetail.sdo?docId=BD-16-1030-0H100-0H002-00000005477&external=true&parentUrl=bid|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref>However, this project was indefinitely postponed until on November 18, 2019, MassDOT announced that this route will not be changing the exit numbers.<ref name=\"Postpone\">{{cite web|author=Robert H. Malme|year=2017|title=Massachusetts Interstate Highway Exit Lists|url=http://www.malmeroads.net/mass21c/intexits.html|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Massachusetts highway exits to be renumbered by January 2022 | website=[[The Boston Globe]] | first=Sofia | last=Saric | date=November 18, 2019 | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/11/18/massachusetts-highway-exits-renumbered-january/s9c8qw1GUBazeuP841JpkO/story.html | access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Renumbering\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newmassexits.com/MassDOT_Documents/Project_Documents/Handout_1.pdf|title = Milepost-based Exit Renumbering|publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation|date=December 5, 2019|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{jcttop|exit|state=MA|county=Hampden|length_ref=<ref name=\"MA Route Log\">{{cite web|url=http://services.massdot.state.ma.us/mrla/RouteSelection.htm|title=Massachusetts Route Log Application|author=MassDOT Planning Division|date=|website=|publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation|accessdate=August 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826161150/http://services.massdot.state.ma.us/mrla/RouteSelection.htm|archive-date=August 26, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>|location_ref=<ref name=\"MA Route Log\" />}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|location=Springfield\n|lspan=8\n|mile=0.000\n<!--\n|old=1A\n|exit=0A\n-->\n|exit=1A\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|91|dir1=south|location1=[[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford, CT]]}}\n|notes=Exit 8 on I-91; [[directional T interchange|tri-stack interchange]].\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=0.463\n<!--\n|old=1B\n|exit=0B\n-->\n|exit=1B\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|91|dir1=north|US|20|dir2=west|city1=West Springfield}}\n|notes=Exit 8 on I-91; western end of concurrency with US&nbsp;20\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=0.589\n<!--\n|old=2A\n|exit=1A\n|notes=Signed as Exit&nbsp;1 eastbound; shares ramp with Exit&nbsp;0A westbound; no access from I-91 north\n-->\n|exit=2A\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Chestnut Street\n|notes=Signed as Exit&nbsp;2 eastbound; shares ramp with Exit&nbsp;1A westbound; no access from I-91 north\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=0.463\n<!--\n|old=2B\n|exit=1B\n|notes=Shares ramp with Exit&nbsp;0B westbound; no access from I-91 south\n-->\n|exit=2B\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Dwight Street\n|notes=Shares ramp with Exit&nbsp;1B westbound; no access from I-91 south\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=1.340\n<!--\n|old=3\n|exit=1C\n-->\n|exit=3\n|road=Armory Street\n|notes=}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=2.410\n<!--\n|old=4\n|exit=2\n-->\n|exit=4\n|road=St. James Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=4.046\n<!--\n|old=5A\n|exit=4A\n-->\n|exit=5A\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|dir1=east|city1=Indian Orchard}}\n|notes=Signed as exit 5 southbound; Eastern end of concurrency with US&nbsp;20\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=4.057\n<!--\n|old=5B\n|exit=4B\n-->\n|exit=5B\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|20A|dir1=west|city1=East Springfield}}\n|notes=Southbound exit is combined with Exit 5\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|location=Chicopee\n|lspan=3\n|mile=5.027\n<!--\n|old=6\n|exit=5A\n-->\n|exit=6\n|road=Fuller Road&nbsp;&ndash; [[Ludlow, Massachusetts|Ludlow]], [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|type=toll\n|mile=5.218\n<!--\n|old=7\n|exit=5B\n-->\n|exit=7\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|90|name1=[[Mass Pike]]|location1=[[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]]|city2=Boston|location3=[[Albany, New York|Albany, NY]]}}\n|notes=Exit&nbsp;6 on I-90\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=5.52\n<!--\n|old=\u2013\n-->\n|exit=\u2013\n|road=Burnett Road north\n|notes=\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=incomplete,concur,toll}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AttachedKML|display=title,inline}}\n{{Commons cat|Interstate 291 (Massachusetts)}}\n*[http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/I-291_MA/ I-291 Historical Overview] from bostonroads.com\n*[http://www.kurumi.com/roads/3di/ix91.html#291ma I-291] - kurumi.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050414032344/http://homepage.mac.com/kefkafloyd/valleyroads/291.html I-291] - Roads and Highways of the Pioneer Valley and Western Massachusetts\n*[http://www.malmeroads.net/mass21c/i291exits.html I-291 Exit Numbers List]\n\n{{3di|91}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interstate 91-2 (Massachusetts)}}\n[[Category:Auxiliary Interstate Highways|91-2 Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in Massachusetts|91-2]]\n[[Category:Interstate 91]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Springfield, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Chicopee, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hampden County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Highway in Massachusetts}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|route=291\n|alternate_name=Springfield Expressway\n|type=I\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|frame-lat=42.135|frame-long=-72.573|zoom=12|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 291 (Massachusetts)}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=I-291 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=5.44\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"fhwa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/reports/routefinder/table2.htm|title=Route Log - Auxiliary Routes of the Eisenhower National System of Interstate and Defense Highways - Table 2|publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]]|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>\n|established=1971<ref name=\"completion\">{{cite web| publisher= AA Roads Interstate Guide| url= http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-291_ma.html#east_end |title= Interstate-Guide: Interstate 291 Massachusetts| accessdate= January 1, 2014}}\n* {{cite news|title=Junkyards, old factories line 291|last=Briere|first=Glen A.|date=September 12, 1971|page=24|work=Springfield Union|location=Springfield, Mass.}}</ref>\n|spur_type=I\n|spur_of=91\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MA|I|91}} in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|20|MA|20A|nolink2=y}} in Springfield\n*{{jct|state=MA|I|90|MATP}} in Chicopee\n}}\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b=Burnett Road in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]]\n|counties=[[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]]\n|previous_type=I\n|previous_route=290\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=295\n}}\n[[Image:Interstate 291 eastbound, Springfield MA.jpg|thumb|right|250px|<center>Eastbound</center>]]\n'''Interstate 291''' (abbreviated '''I-291'''), also known as the '''Springfield Expressway''',<ref name=\"bostonroads\">[http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/I-291_MA/ Springfield Expressway (I-291)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> is a {{convert|5.44|mi|km|adj=on}} connector highway in [[Massachusetts]] that links [[Interstate 91]] in downtown [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]] with [[Interstate 90 in Massachusetts|Interstate 90]] (the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]) in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]]. I-291 is roughly a northeast/southwest highway. It merges with I-91 at its southwestern terminus, via a flyover. The road meets the Mass Pike at its northeastern terminus. Getting onto the Pike from I-291 is straightforward, but getting from the Pike to I-291 requires a left turn at an at-grade traffic signal. I-291 travels directly through highly populated areas of Springfield, and passes under several overpasses. From its southwestern terminus to exit 5A, Interstate 291 is [[Concurrency (road)|concurrent]] with [[U.S. Route 20]].\n\nI-291 is only {{convert|22.4|mi|km}} from [[Interstate 291 (Connecticut)|Interstate 291]] in [[Connecticut]], and there are no intervening Interstate Highway interchanges between them. It can be easy for travelers to become confused between the two highways.{{fact|date=January 2009}}\n\n==Route description==\nInterstate 291 begins as a spur of Interstate 91 at Exit 8 in Springfield, concurrent with U.S. 20, which merges from the north. The two entry ramps from I-91 merge with each other after Exits 2A and 2B, where a sign for the beginning of I-291 east is posted. I-291 and U.S. 20 run eastbound concurrently until Exit 5A (U.S. 20 joins westbound at Exit 5), where U.S. 20 east leaves the highway for a junction with [[Massachusetts Route 20A|Route 20A]]. I-291 continues east into Chicopee, where it intersects the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] ([[Interstate 90]]).  I-291 ends at an odd intersection at a stoplight on Burnett Road, but I-291 east traffic can exit uninterrupted by way of a ramp to the Mass Pike. However, drivers coming from the Mass Pike must deal with this traffic light, as a left turn across the intersection is required to get on I-291 west.\n\nThe westbound interchange with I-91 is unusual in that the ramps for Exit 1A-B split before the ramps for Exits 2A-B do.  Traffic bound for Exit 2A (Chestnut Street) must first take the ramp for Exit 1A (I-91 South), and traffic bound for Exit 2B (Dwight St.) must first take the ramp for Exit 1B (I-91 North).\n\nTraffic bound for U.S. 20 West from I-291 takes Exit 1B. U.S. 20 does not actually join with I-91, but rather this exit splits, left for the on-ramp to I-91 North, the right to continue on the U.S. 20 access ramp.\n\n==History==\nI-291 was originally conceived in 1953, prior to the creation of the Interstate Highway System, as the Springfield Expressway, which would bypass [[U.S. Route 20 in Massachusetts|US 20]] and connect to the [[U.S. Route 5 in Massachusetts|US 5 expressway]] (now I-91) and the proposed [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]. I-291 follows the original planned alignment of the expressway, except for the stretch between exit 4 (St. James Avenue) and exit 5 (US 20/MA 20A/Page Boulevard). The original planned alignment had the route turn in almost a perfect 90 degree angle onto Roosevelt Avenue, but industrial development (including the relocation of [[Smith & Wesson]]'s corporate headquarters) had the highway turn more gently. The first section of the expressway that was built was the bridge over the [[Chicopee River]].<ref>{{cite web| publisher= Boston Roads |url= http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/I-291_MA/ |title= Springfield Expressway (I-291)| accessdate= January 1, 2014}}</ref> The first section of the expressway that opened was from US 20/MA 20A to I-90 (Mass. Turnpike) in 1957; work on the freeway started up again in 1967 and the entire highway was completed in 1971.<ref name=\"completion\"/> The construction delay was due to I-91 having priority through western Massachusetts.\n\n==Exit list==\nAll interchanges were to be renumbered to mileage-based numbers under a project scheduled to start in 2016.<ref name=\"Exit Numbers\">{{cite web|author=Commonwealth of Massachusetts|year=2015|title=COMMBUYS - Bid Solicitation FAP# HSIP-002S(874) Exit Signage Conversion to Milepost-Based Numbering System along Various Interstates, Routes and the Lowell Connector |url=https://www.commbuys.com/bso/external/bidDetail.sdo?docId=BD-16-1030-0H100-0H002-00000005477&external=true&parentUrl=bid|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref>However, this project was indefinitely postponed until on November 18, 2019, MassDOT announced that this route will not be changing the exit numbers.<ref name=\"Postpone\">{{cite web|author=Robert H. Malme|year=2017|title=Massachusetts Interstate Highway Exit Lists|url=http://www.malmeroads.net/mass21c/intexits.html|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Massachusetts highway exits to be renumbered by January 2022 | website=[[The Boston Globe]] | first=Sofia | last=Saric | date=November 18, 2019 | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/11/18/massachusetts-highway-exits-renumbered-january/s9c8qw1GUBazeuP841JpkO/story.html | access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Renumbering\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newmassexits.com/MassDOT_Documents/Project_Documents/Handout_1.pdf|title = Milepost-based Exit Renumbering|publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation|date=December 5, 2019|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{jcttop|exit|state=MA|county=Hampden|length_ref=<ref name=\"MA Route Log\">{{cite web|url=http://services.massdot.state.ma.us/mrla/RouteSelection.htm|title=Massachusetts Route Log Application|author=MassDOT Planning Division|date=|website=|publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation|accessdate=August 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826161150/http://services.massdot.state.ma.us/mrla/RouteSelection.htm|archive-date=August 26, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>|location_ref=<ref name=\"MA Route Log\" />}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|location=Springfield\n|lspan=8\n|mile=0.000\n<!--\n|old=1A\n|exit=0A\n-->\n|exit=1A\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|91|dir1=south|location1=[[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford, CT]]}}\n|notes=Exit 8 on I-91; [[directional T interchange|tri-stack interchange]].\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=0.463\n<!--\n|old=1B\n|exit=0B\n-->\n|exit=1B\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|91|dir1=north|US|20|dir2=west|city1=West Springfield}}\n|notes=Exit 8 on I-91; western end of concurrency with US&nbsp;20\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=0.589\n<!--\n|old=2A\n|exit=1A\n|notes=Signed as Exit&nbsp;1 eastbound; shares ramp with Exit&nbsp;0A westbound; no access from I-91 north\n-->\n|exit=2A\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Chestnut Street\n|notes=Signed as Exit&nbsp;2 eastbound; shares ramp with Exit&nbsp;1A westbound; no access from I-91 north\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=0.463\n<!--\n|old=2B\n|exit=1B\n|notes=Shares ramp with Exit&nbsp;0B westbound; no access from I-91 south\n-->\n|exit=2B\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Dwight Street\n|notes=Shares ramp with Exit&nbsp;1B westbound; no access from I-91 south\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=1.340\n<!--\n|old=3\n|exit=1C\n-->\n|exit=3\n|road=Armory Street\n|notes=}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=2.410\n<!--\n|old=4\n|exit=2\n-->\n|exit=4\n|road=St. James Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=4.046\n<!--\n|old=5A\n|exit=4A\n-->\n|exit=5A\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|dir1=east|city1=Indian Orchard}}\n|notes=Signed as exit 5 southbound; Eastern end of concurrency with US&nbsp;20\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=4.057\n<!--\n|old=5B\n|exit=4B\n-->\n|exit=5B\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|20A|dir1=west|city1=East Springfield}}\n|notes=Southbound exit is combined with Exit 5\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|location=Chicopee\n|lspan=3\n|mile=5.027\n<!--\n|old=6\n|exit=5A\n-->\n|exit=6\n|road=Fuller Road&nbsp;&ndash; [[Ludlow, Massachusetts|Ludlow]], [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|type=toll\n|mile=5.218\n<!--\n|old=7\n|exit=5B\n-->\n|exit=7\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|90|name1=[[Mass Pike]]|city1=Boston|location2=[[Albany, New York|Albany, NY]]}}\n|notes=Exit&nbsp;6 on I-90\n}}\n{{MAint|exit\n|mile=5.52\n<!--\n|old=\u2013\n-->\n|exit=\u2013\n|road=Burnett Road north\n|notes=\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=incomplete,concur,toll}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AttachedKML|display=title,inline}}\n{{Commons cat|Interstate 291 (Massachusetts)}}\n*[http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/I-291_MA/ I-291 Historical Overview] from bostonroads.com\n*[http://www.kurumi.com/roads/3di/ix91.html#291ma I-291] - kurumi.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050414032344/http://homepage.mac.com/kefkafloyd/valleyroads/291.html I-291] - Roads and Highways of the Pioneer Valley and Western Massachusetts\n*[http://www.malmeroads.net/mass21c/i291exits.html I-291 Exit Numbers List]\n\n{{3di|91}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interstate 91-2 (Massachusetts)}}\n[[Category:Auxiliary Interstate Highways|91-2 Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in Massachusetts|91-2]]\n[[Category:Interstate 91]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Springfield, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Chicopee, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hampden County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "2601:192:103:3000:5c62:df69:d586:d315", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interstate_291_(Massachusetts)"}
{"title_page": "1955 System", "text_new": "''<nowiki/>''\n\nThe '''''1955 system''' (55\u5e74\u4f53\u5236),'' also known as the 'one-and-a-half party system', refers to the party system in Japan from 1955 to 1993 in which the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP) successively held majority government while the major opposition the [[Japan Socialist Party]] (JSP) was incapable of forming an alternative. The terms ''1955 system'' and ''one-and-a-half system'' are credited to Junnosuke Masumi who describes the system of 1955 as \"a grand political dam into which the history of Japanese politics surge.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=Gendai seiji : 1955-nen igo|last=1926-2010.|first=Masumi, Junnosuke|last2=1926-2010.|first2=\u5347\u5473\u6e96\u4e4b\u8f14|date=1985|publisher=T\u014dky\u014d Daigaku Shuppankai|isbn=978-4130330268|edition=Shohan|location=T\u014dky\u014d|oclc=15423787}}</ref> The years of Japan under 1955 regime witnessed the [[Japanese economic miracle|economic miracle]], but also the dominance of the ruling party in the [[National Diet|Diet]], with an undergirded tight connection between the bureaucracy and the business sector. Due to a series of LDP scandals and the 1992 burst of [[Japanese asset price bubble]], LDP lost its majority in the [[House of Representatives of Japan|House of Representatives]] in the [[1993 Japanese general election|1993 general election]].\n\n''<nowiki/>''\n\n''<nowiki/>''\n\n''<nowiki/>''\n\n== Background ==\n\n=== Pre-1955 Multiparty System ===\n[[File:Japanese_General_election,_1947_en.svg|alt=|thumb|250x250px|House of Representatives Seat Distribution in 1947]]\nAfter World War II, Japan was controlled by the [[Supreme Commander for the Allied Powers]] (SCAP). SCAP aimed at the eradication of militarism and the promotion of democratization in Japan, and therefore it issues a series of policies to arrest suspected war criminals which shuffled the political power in Japan.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite book|title=Politics in modern Japan : development and organization|last=1928-|first=Kishimoto, K\u014dichi|date=1997|publisher=Japan Echo|isbn=978-4915226076|location=|pages=21\u201323|oclc=38224699}}</ref> The power of right-wing parties declined in the immediate post war periods due to the purge. The [[Japan Progressive Party]] lost about 90% of the seats in the purge, while the [[Liberal Party (Japan, 1950)|Japan Liberal Party]] lost about 45%. Meanwhile, since many parties on the left were only legalized under the command of SCAP after the WW2, they were barely influenced by the purge.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|title=The making of modern Japan|last=B.|first=Jansen, Marius|date=2000|publisher=Belknap Press of Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0674003347|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/makingofmodernja00jans/page/675 675]|oclc=44090600|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/makingofmodernja00jans/page/675}}</ref> As a result, the [[Socialist Party of Japan|Socialist Party]] ''(\u65e5\u672c\u793e\u4f1a\u515a)'' led by [[Tetsu Katayama]] ''(\u7247\u5c71\u54f2)'' won the [[1947 Japanese general election|first general election]] after the enforcement of the constitution of Japan.\n\nAlthough at the time no formal regulations about how to form a coalition government existed, there was a consensus among the major parties that a coalition government should be formed to manage the post-war economic problems. Nonetheless, which party would be included in the coalition took a long process of negotiations. Both a four-party coalition excluding the Communist Party and a three-party coalition excluding both the [[Japanese Communist Party|Communist Party]] and the Liberal Party were suggested within the socialists. The Liberal party, led by anticommunist [[Shigeru Yoshida]] ''(\u5409\u7530\u8302)'', showed great reluctance of joining the coalition.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|title=Japan's postwar party politics|last=1962-|first=Kohno, Masaru|date=1997|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0691026299|location=|pages=50\u201353|oclc=441854586}}</ref> At a meeting between the Katayama and Yoshida in May 19, 1947, the Liberal Party asked Katayama to \u201cbreak off with the leftists\u201d in return of its participation in the coalition. Since the Socialist Party had already claimed to officially cut ties with the Communist Party earlier, it refused such demand.<ref name=\":62\">{{Cite book|title=\u4e94\u4e94\u5e74\u4f53\u5236\u3068\u65e5\u672c\u793e\u4f1a\u515a|last=\u6881\u7530|first=\u6d69\u797a|publisher=\u3042\u308a\u3048\u3059\u66f8\u623f|year=1981|isbn=|location=\u6771\u4eac|pages=81\u201384}}</ref> The lengthy coalition-building process ended up with a government headed by the Socialist Party, the Democratic Party, and the [[National Cooperative Party]].<ref name=\":42\" />\n\nThe Katayama-led coalition government did not last more than a year due to opposition from both inside the Socialist Party and outside. In order to form a coalition, Katayama had to make concessions which departed from original policy proposals, which further facilitated the split between the leftist faction and the rightist faction within the party. At the same time, policies which Katayama did implement, such as nationalization of coal and mine production, drove the conservatives away.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n=== Yoshida Hegemony ===\n[[File:Japanese_General_election,_1949_en.svg|thumb|246x246px|House of Representatives Seat Distribution in 1949]]\nAfter the failure of Katayama cabinet, voters lost confidence in the Socialist Party, which led to the takeover of government by Yoshida Shigeru. In the [[1949 Japanese general election|general election of 1949]], the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Japan)|Democratic Liberal Party]] led by Yoshida won a majority in the House of representatives with 269 seats out of 466 seats, while the Socialist Party won only 48 seats. This was the first majority cabinet in post-war Japan.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Postwar Japan : 1945 to the present|last=J.|first=Bayley, Paul|date=1996|publisher=Blackwell|isbn=978-0631179016|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/postwarjapan19450000bail/page/58 58]|oclc=807111830|url=https://archive.org/details/postwarjapan19450000bail/page/58}}</ref>\n\nYoshida Shigeru organized five cabinets as a prime minister between 1946 to 1954. The diplomatic, economic, and security policies which Yoshida adopted when he was in power were altogether referred as the \u201c[[Yoshida Doctrine]]\u201d.<ref name=\":72\">{{Cite journal|last=Sugita|first=Yoneyuki|date=2016|title=The Yoshida Doctrine as a Myth|url=http://www.jaas.gr.jp/jjas/pdf/2016/06_SUGIYAMA.pdf|journal=The Japanese Journal of American Studies|volume=27|pages=|via=}}</ref> These policies remained influential even after him being voted out of the office by a no-confidence motion by the \u201cYoshida students\u201d who followed his ideology.<ref name=\":02\" /> The Yoshida Doctrine has three major components: 1. Japan relies on its alliance with the U.S. for national security; 2. Japan preserves a low level of self-defense capacity; 3. Japan should concentrate on the reconstruction of domestic economy.<ref name=\":72\" /> The Yoshida Doctrine set the tone for Japan\u2019s economic miracle and alignment with the West. However, Yoshida\u2019s \u201cone man\u201d leadership and anti-communist stance was criticized and eventually led to the defection of many Diet members from his party to the new [[Democratic Party (Japan, 1954)|Democratic Party]], causing his cabinet to resign on December 7, 1954.<ref name=\":52\" />\n\n=== Fall of Yoshida Shigeru ===\n[[File:Brawling_diet_2.JPG|thumb|227x227px|Dietmembers brawl due to the steamrolling of the amendment to the Police Act.]]\nThe criticisms of Yoshida cabinet mainly focused on three issues:\n\n# In 1951, The [[Treaty of San Francisco|San Francisco Peace Treaty]] and the [[Security Treaty Between the United States and Japan]] was signed under Yoshida cabinet. The Peace Treaty was signed without the communist bloc\u2019s presence, which was condemned by the Communist Party for its anti-communist stance. The Security Treaty was criticized by both the Communist Party and the Socialist Party for the risk of remilitarization, while also criticized by the conservatives for putting Japan in a subordinate position, since Japan was asked to provide military base for the U.S.\u2019s force.<ref name=\":82\">{{Cite book|title=\u6226\u5f8c\u6539\u9769\u3068\u9006\u30b3\u30fc\u30b9|last=\u5409\u7530|first=\u88d5|publisher=\u5409\u5ddd\u5f18\u6587\u9928|year=2004|isbn=|location=\u6771\u4eac|pages=81\u201385}}</ref>\n# During the fifth Yoshida cabinet, several bills were passed with the strong opposition of the Leftist Socialist Party of Japan and the Rightist Socialist Party of Japan, including the Strike Control Act, the Mutual Defense Assistance Agreement between Japan and the United States of America, two education acts which restrict the political participation of school teachers, amendment to the Police Act, Self-Defense Forces Act. Among which, the amendment to the Police Act was steamrolled with the opposition parties absent from the Diet.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=\u4e94\u4e94\u5e74\u4f53\u5236\u3068\u5b89\u4fdd\u95d8\u4e89|last=\u6b74\u53f2\u5b66\u7814\u7a76\u4f1a|publisher=\u9752\u6728\u66f8\u5e97|year=1990|isbn=|location=\u6771\u4eac|pages=82}}</ref>\n# The Yoshida cabinet was also involved in two major corruption cases. One is known as the Hozen Keizai Kai Incident ''(\u4fdd\u5168\u7d4c\u6e08\u4f1a\u4e8b\u4ef6)''. Masutomi Ito, the director of a financial institution Hozen Keizai Kai which, was accused of fraud and suspected of making political bribery, which resulted in the arrests of several conservative politicians.<ref name=\":22\" /> The other is known as the Shipbuilding Bribery ''(\u9020\u8239\u7591\u7344)'', in which the shipping business and shipbuilding business were proved to be making pay-off to conservative politicians. Influential politicians in the ruling party such as [[Eisaku Sat\u014d|Eisaku Sato]] ''(\u4f50\u85e4\u6804\u4f5c)'' and [[Hayato Ikeda]] ''(\u6c60\u7530\u52c7\u4eba)'' were suspected as bribe takers. The Yoshida cabinet reacted to this incident by stopping the arrest of Eisaku Sato.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://showa.mainichi.jp/news/1954/04/post-1e45.html|title=\u9020\u8239\u7591\u7344\u3067\u6307\u63ee\u6a29\u767a\u52d5|last=|first=|date=21 April 1954|work=\u6bce\u65e5\u65b0\u805e|access-date=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe three controversies led to the gathering of anti-Yoshida forces. On October 20, 1954, anti-Yoshida conservatives formed a coalition party: the [[Democratic Party (Japan, 1954)|Japan Democratic Party]] ''(\u65e5\u672c\u6c11\u4e3b\u515a)''. The Japan Democratic Party along with the Leftist Socialist Party of Japan and the Rightist Socialist Party of Japan tabled a [[Motion of no confidence|no-confidence motion]] against the cabinet on December 6 and won the majority. As a result, Yoshida Cabinet resigned on December 7 after six years of rule.\n\n== Establishment of the 1955 System ==\n\n=== Merger of the Japan Socialist Party (JSP) ===\nWithin the Socialist party, ideological conflicts had long been a problem. The leftists in the party adopted a Marx-Lenin ideology as China, while the rightists leaned towards a socialist welfare nation under a capitalist system. The San Francisco Peace Treaty and the Security Treaty Between the United States and Japan signed in 1951 triggered the final split. The right socialists agreed on the San Francisco Peace Treaty but were against the Security Treaty, due to their constitutionalist stance, while the left socialists were against both treaties due to their exclusion of Soviet Union.<ref name=\":02\" /> On October 23, 1951, the old Socialist Party officially split into the [[Leftist Socialist Party of Japan]] ''(\u5de6\u6d3e\u793e\u4f1a\u515a)'' and the [[Rightist Socialist Party of Japan]] ''(\u53f3\u6d3e\u793e\u4f1a\u515a)''.\n\nAfter the split, however, the socialists soon realized the necessity of merging into one party to fight against the anti-communist approach taken by the GHQ and the conservatives, which is commonly referred to as the [[Reverse Course|reverse course]] ''(\u9006\u30b3\u30fc\u30b9)''. After the San Francisco Peace Treaty came into effect, influential members from the Rightist Socialist Party of Japan came back from the purge and boosted the power of the rightists. The Leftist Socialist Party of Japan also expanded its power with the support of the [[General Council of Trade Unions of Japan]], also known as ''Sohyo(\u65e5\u672c\u52b4\u50cd\u7d44\u5408\u7dcf\u8a55\u8b70\u4f1a)''. Meanwhile, the conservatives were suffering criticisms from the public for the corruption scandals and Security Treaty. Sensing the possibility of success, despite their ideological differences, to take power from the political right and fight against the anti-communist movement, the socialists decided to reunite and formed the Japan Socialist Party (JSP) on October 13, 1955.<ref name=\":62\" />\n[[File:Japanese_General_election,_1955_en.svg|left|thumb|257x257px|Before the merger: House of Representative Seat Distribution in 1955]]\nOne crucial external factor that caused the merger of JSD is ''Sohyo''. ''Sohyo'', the abbreviation of the General Council of Trade Unions of Japan, was a trade confederation in Japan which was established on July 11, 1950, soon after the start of the Korean War. It incorporated about 48% of organized workers in Japan. Initially, ''Sohyo''was the unified body of anti-communist unions, but it soon changed from a centralist stance to a left stance due to the remilitarization tendency of Japan shown in the Korean War.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Incorporating Japanese labor into the Free World: Cold War diplomacy and economic interdependence, 1949\u20131964|journal = Labor History|volume = 49|issue = 2|pages = 199\u2013222|last=Nakakita|first=Koji|date=2008|doi=10.1080/00236560801950972}}</ref> Due to the rationalization strategy taken by the conservative government, Japanese workers, particular those worked in small and median-sized factories were facing slow wage increase and even dismissals. In response, ''Sohyo'' organized the anti-rationalization campaign and pressured the merger of JSP.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Disparaged success : labor politics in postwar Japan|last=1957-|first=Kume, Ikuo|date=1998|publisher=Cornell Univ. Press|isbn=978-0801433641|oclc=833127781|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/disparagedsucces0000kume}}</ref>\n[[File:Japanese_General_election,_1958_en.svg|left|thumb|257x257px|After the merger: House of Representatives Seat Distribution in 1958]]\n\n=== Merger of the Liberal Democratic Party of Japan (LDP) ===\nIn the [[1955 Japanese general election|1955 general election]], the conservative Japan Democratic Party won the ruling position. Meanwhile, the Leftist Socialist Party of Japan was able to win 17 more seats. The expansion of Leftist Socialist Party of Japan and the soon formation of the leftists and rightists in the socialist camp into JSP became a more substantial threat for the conservatives. As a result, also in 1955, the Japan Democratic Party and the Japan Liberal Party merged as Liberal Democratic Party of Japan (LDP).<ref name=\":82\" />\n\nThe expansion of the socialist power also worried the ''Zaikai''(business community). ''Zaikai'' had incentives to secure a conservative government since it would pump money into the big companies to keep their competitiveness, stay in a close relationship with the U.S. to maintain a liberal trade policy, and deal with the intensified anti-rationalization labor movement. Therefore, to counter the socialist power, the ''Zaikai'' pressured the Liberal Party and the Democratic Party to merge.<ref name=\":92\">{{Cite journal|last=Masumi|first=Junnosuke|date=1988|title=The 1955 System in Japan and Its Subsequent Development|journal=Asian Survey|volume=28|issue=3|pages=286\u2013306|doi=10.1525/as.1988.28.3.01p0146p|issn=0004-4687|url=http://as.ucpress.edu/content/ucpas/28/3/286.full.pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Outcome of the merger: 1955 System ===\nAfter the formation of the two major parties, JSP and LDP, a [[1958 Japanese general election|general election]] was held in 1958. Although the Socialist Party was gaining more power at the time, the conservative Liberal Party and Democratic Party had more voters from the beginning, not to mention after the merge of the two. As a result, the LDP won almost as twice as many seats as JSP. The 1955 system, also known as \u201cone and a half system\u201d, was established, in which LDP always as the dominant party and JSP never able to be a strong enough alternative.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|title=The politics of electoral systems|date=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Gallagher, Michael, 1951-, Mitchell, Paul, 1964-|isbn=9780191531514|location=Oxford|oclc=68623713}}</ref>\n\n1955 system essentially was the symbol of the two parties\u2019 confrontation over two major issues: the [[Constitution of Japan|1946 constitution]] and the security treaty.<ref name=\":92\" /> During the occupation years, Minister Matsumoto Joji ''(\u677e\u672c\u70dd\u6cbb)'' drafted the 1946 constitution under the demand of General [[Douglas MacArthur]]. Unsatisfied with the draft, the draft was later then revised by the SCAP. Therefore, the 1946 constitution was more of American authorship and the banner for SCAP\u2019s goal of democratization of Japan. The conservative parties had the consideration of constitution revision since its enactment. Although varying in extent, the revision of [[Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution|Article 9]] to permit a rearmament program had been widely argued with the conservative parties since the Yoshida cabinet. At the same time, the socialist parties opposed any revision of the constitution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ward|first=Robert E.|date=1956|title=The Constitution and Current Japanese Politics|journal=Far Eastern Survey|volume=25|issue=4|pages=49\u201358|doi=10.2307/3023907|issn=0362-8949|jstor=3023907}}</ref>\n\nAnother issue was the security Treaty signed in 1951, a product of the late occupation years. Different from the 1946 constitution which aims at wiping out the [[Japanese militarism|militarism in Japan]], the Security Treaty was the consequence of U.S. securing its military strength in Asia to counter the communist threat in the [[Cold War]]. JSP strongly opposed the Security Treaty due to the underlying possibility of further rearmament and even revival militarism in Japan, while LDP argued that the presence of the U.S. army in Japan was merely for self-defense.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Protest in tokyo - the security treaty crisis of 1960.|last=R.|first=Packard, George|year=|isbn=9780691650746|location=|pages=3\u201322|oclc=1023228016}}</ref>\n\n== LDP dominance in the 1955 system ==\n\n=== Electoral system ===\nThe electoral system that was used under 1955 system is known as the [[Single non-transferable vote|Single Nontransferable Vote]] (SNTV). Under SNTV, each constituency has multiple seats to be filled. Voters instead of voting for parties, votes for individual candidates, and seats of the constituency go to whoever wins the most votes. One problem of such electoral system is that the fair allocation of seats to different parties are not taken into consideration: Since the winners of most votes eventually get the seats, candidates of one party can take all the seats of one constituency.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nUnder such electoral system, LDP with its massive political donation put other opposition parties into disadvantage. Due to LDP\u2019s ties with big companies, the party directed the financial resources to individual candidates and enabled them to promise patronage to their voters, with a focus on the agricultural population, while the reallocation of Diet seats did not keep up with the migration from rural to urban area due to industrialization. Aside from the pork-barrel spending, the LDP candidates also cultivated personalism through [[Koenkai]] ''(\u5f8c\u63f4\u4f1a)'' in their own constituency. Politicians went to the locals\u2019 wedding, funeral, birthday parties and so on. In such occasions, politicians often brought considerable amount of cash gift. Candidates would even organize activities such as hot springs for their supporters.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOn the account of its self-assertiveness, LDP unilaterally altered the rules for campaigning. Profiting of its constituted koenkai canvas, the competition rules were toughened for the Opposition. The formal campaign periods were short (and shortened further over time), television and radio advertising being prohibited and low limits placed on posters and handbills. Through the campaign, however, each candidate was granted two five-minute slots on television when a stream of candidates would line up and take turns in front of a stationary microphone to run through their list of promises right after which the next candidate would take other. Such rules of play were discouraging and difficult for a would-be challenger while LDP benefitted from the unfair restraints of participation by the sheer amount of runners.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Japanese party system : from one-party rule to coalition government|last=1945-|first=Hrebenar, Ronald J.|date=1986|publisher=Westview Press|others=Berton, Peter, 1922-2014.|isbn=978-0813303468|location=Boulder, Colo.|oclc=13455801}}</ref>\n\nAnother neglected flaw of the electoral system which bolstered LDP's dominance was the urgent need for redistricting in the wake of the post-war rapid population shifts from the rural to urban areas. The swelling urban populations were much trickier for LDP politicians to fit within the distributed koenkai grassroot structure as they were more peripatetic and atomized than the traditional rural household. These voters had new policy demands (ex. issues related to [[Environmental issues in Japan#Environment deterioration in the 1960s|environmental deterioration in the 1960s]]) which conflicted with the ones practiced by LDP for their industry and big-business support. Under the obsolete district constituencies, the farmers retained disproportionate political influence which as a consequence of pork-barrel desires rather than by concern over issues of broad social policy, stagnated democratic alternation.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite book|title=Japan transformed : political change and economic restructuring|last=McCall.|first=Rosenbluth, Frances |author-link=Frances McCall Rosenbluth|date=2010|publisher=Princeton University Press|others=Thies, Michael F.|isbn=9780691135915|location=Princeton, N.J.|oclc=428926469}}</ref>\n\nUnder the current electoral rules, LDP was motivated to develop loyal personal support for the farmer's voter group. Being a nationally organized group of voters and united around the single issue of agricultural protectionism, the party could tune higher import tariffs and subsidies to support the less productive small businesses which because of their large numbers, could turn out at elections and vote in predictable ways.\n\n=== Bureaucratization of policymaking ===\nSince the institution of the 1955 system, the legislative independence has been declining in the face of a growth in the combined legislative power of the bureaucracy and the ruling conservative party. Indicators that point to this are the success rates of governmental and individual member bills; the declining rate of amendments added; and the singular lack of success for opposition-sponsored bills. For example, the mere submission of nongovernmentally sponsored measures is extremely difficult. In the [[House of Representatives (Japan)|Lower House]], at least 20 representatives must support a \"member\" bill before it can be introduced, while in the [[House of Councillors (Japan)|Upper House]] ten supporters are required. Moreover, should the bill require the expenditure of state funds, fifty and twenty supporters respectively are necessary.\n\nThe chance for success of bureaucratic bills that was only 1.3 times greater than that for individual Diet-generated bills under the [[Occupation of Japan|Occupation]] and about twice as great from 1952 to 1955, it augmented to 7 times greater by 1974, when approximately 90% of all successful legislation has been cabinet-sponsored.<ref name=\":102\">{{Cite journal|last=Pempel|first=T. J.|date=November 1974|title=The Bureaucratization of Policymaking in Postwar Japan|journal=American Journal of Political Science|volume=18|issue=4|pages=647\u2013664|doi=10.2307/2110551|issn=0092-5853|jstor=2110551}}</ref> In addition, the Diet has not been notably active as a potential amender for which there are two devices open: it can either \"amend\" (''shusei''), or it can \"add supplementary resolution of clarification\" (''futai ketsugi''). From 1955 to 1960 just over one-third of all successful government legislation went through one or another of these processes. In the 48th Diet (1964-1965) this rate was 17% and in the 63rd Diet (1970) it was 15%. Finally, opposition bills had no chance of success: of 317 opposition bills introduced from the 37th (1960) through the 46th (1963-1964) Diets, not one became law.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Misawa|first=Shigeo|date=1967-05-30|journal=The Annuals of Japanese Political Science Association|volume=18|pages=5\u201333, 2|doi=10.7218/nenpouseijigaku1953.18.0_5|issn=0549-4192|title=Outline of Policy-Decision Making Process Since 1955|doi-access=free}}</ref> These numbers attest that by the time bills materialize in the Diet a general agreement has already been reached, both within and between the bureaucracy and the LDP. In such an environment, opposition and the generation of successful alternatives from within the Diet itself has become extremely difficult.<ref name=\":102\" />\n\nBesides, the bureaucracy wields considerable and increasing power through the use of nonlegislative devices such a subordinances and communications, and through its varying degrees of dominance over technical and nonpartisan advisory groups.<ref name=\":102\" />\n\n=== Policy decision-making ===\nThe [[Policy Affairs Research Council]] (\u653f\u52d9\u8abf\u67fb\u4f1a ''seimu ch\u014dsakai'') or \"PARC\" was the major policymaking body within the LDP. Its members were the LDP representatives in both legislative houses, and it was the basic forum in which the party discussed and negotiated government policy. The policymaking under this system did not comply with the usual model of a parliamentary cabinet government which involves strong cabinet leadership and coordination. Instead, representatives who were not in the cabinet were often the other pivot of policy through their formal roles PARC. In consultation with bureaucrats and interest groups, the council already had input into policy before the cabinet and prime minister or upper party executives could shape it further. At its height in the mid-1980s, PARC had as many as seventeen divisions.\n\n==== Industrial policy ====\nJapan's industrial policy under the 1955 system was undergirded by a political logic that supports firms and whole industries that would not have been sustainable in a less-regulated economy, imposed high prices and taxes, limited choice in the marketplace, and rigid career paths.<ref name=\":32\" /> In spite of the fact that Japan came out of war with a theoretical comparative advantage towards light manufacturing which would match its profile of low-capital, abundant-labor economy, the war skewed its economic profile toward heavy industries. The large war companies lobbied for a development strategy favoring heavy industry and received subsidies and regulatory favoritism. In exchange, LDP members were awarded with campaign contributions to be able to stay electorally competitive against each other in the multi-member districts.\n\nThe Heavy Industries Bureau of the [[Ministry of International Trade and Industry]] assisted the heavy industries with policies such as:\n\n* Limiting entry and often regulating the market pricing to help stabilize profits.\n* Privileging access to cheap loans from the Japan Development Bank\n* Domestic government budget subsidies and tax breaks as well as favored access to foreign exchange and tariff protections.\n\nSuch strategy of developmental policy which has strong state involvement in developmental orientation is typical of late industrialing countries and in terms of [[international political economy]], follows the model of the [[developmental state]]. Explicit implication implies a degree of corruption, which during [[Kakuei Tanaka]]'s office in 1971-1972 resulted in media noticing corruption which, in one instance, resulted in the [[Kakuei Tanaka#Lockheed scandal and aftermath|Lockheed scandal]].\n\n== The fall of the system ==\n\n=== Global Pressure and the Collapse of Bubble Economy ===\nAs a corollary of the [[Plaza Accord|Plaza Accord of 1985]] when Japan agreed to allow substantial appreciation of the yen, the Japanese government reduced the interests marginally above the rate of inflation as a domestic relief strategy. This resulted in banks and corporations going on an enormous spending spree with nearly free money, bidding up the price of real estate and other assets.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Unwanted company : foreign investment in American industries|last=1965-|first=Crystal, Jonathan|isbn=9781501723612|location=Ithaca|oclc=1042219263}}</ref>\n\nAgainst the faith of many people that Japan would come to dominate the world economy, the [[Japanese asset price bubble]] led to a bubble crash after the raising of interest rates of the [[Bank of Japan]] in 1990 and firms together with their jobs were in mortal danger. In this context and on the background of LDP's short-term relieved pressure from the already shaky electoral coalition between exporters and the non-traded sectors, the voting public expressed disenchantment toward the ruling Liberal Democratic Party.\n\nThe new electoral system following the [[1994 Japanese electoral reform|1994 Electoral reform]] which was claimed to reduce corruption and high elections costs, promote more policy debates, and encourage a two-party system. As a consequence of this reform as well as the change of voter behavior and the change of the international environment, the system collapsed completely following the [[2005 Japanese general election|2005]] and [[2009 Japanese general election|2009]] general elections which demonstrated significant shifts in both the foundations of party support and the importance of national swings in support for one party or another. Since 2005, urban-rural differences in the foundations of the leading parties have changed dramatically, and Japan has moved from a system dominated by locally based, individual candidacies toward a two-party system in which both party popularity and personal characteristics influence electoral success or failure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thies|first=Michael F.|last2=Scheiner|first2=Ethan|last3=Reed|first3=Steven R.|date=2012-07-14|title=The End of LDP Dominance and the Rise of Party-Oriented Politics in Japan|journal=The Journal of Japanese Studies|volume=38|issue=2|pages=353\u2013376|doi=10.1353/jjs.2012.0037|issn=1549-4721}}</ref>\n\nThe specialist on theoretical knowledge of legislative institutions and electoral systems, Michael Thies, argues that majoritarian institutions of the Anglo-American variety would have pushed politics toward broader coalitions, reducing the premiums captured by organized groups with extreme preferences, and appealing more to the interests of unorganized, diverse voters. A study on the representation of unorganized groups under [[proportional representation]] (featuring multi-member [[Electoral district|voting-districts]]) concludes that closed-list proportional representation makes legislators generally more responsive to interest groups and less responsive to unorganized voters than single-member districts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thies|first=Michael F.|last2=Bawn|first2=Kathleen|date=2003|title=A Comparative Theory of Electoral Incentives: Representing the Unorganized Under PR, Plurality, and Mixed-Member Electoral Systems.|location=Rochester, NY|doi=10.2139/ssrn.1158628|ssrn=1158628}}</ref> An even representation would have given labor a persistent and politically potent voice of the kind seen in continental Europe.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[1947 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1949 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1955 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1958 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1993 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1994 Japanese electoral reform|1994 Electoral reform]]\n* [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]]\n* [[Social Democratic Party (Japan)|Social Democratic Party]]\n* [[Japanese economic miracle]]\n* [[Zaibatsu]]\n* [[Government-business relations in Japan]]\n* [[Kakuei Tanaka|Tanaka Kakuei]]\n* [[Koenkai]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Politics of Post-war Japan]]\n[[Category:Cold War history of Japan]]\n", "text_old": "''<nowiki/>''\n\nThe '''''1955 system''' (55\u5e74\u4f53\u5236),'' also known as the 'one-and-a-half party system', refers to the party system in Japan from 1955 to 1993 in which the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP) successively held majority government while the major opposition the [[Japan Socialist Party]] (JSP) was incapable of forming an alternative. The terms ''1955 system'' and ''one-and-a-half system'' are credited to Junnosuke Masumi who describes the system of 1955 as \"a grand political dam into which the history of Japanese politics surge.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=Gendai seiji : 1955-nen igo|last=1926-2010.|first=Masumi, Junnosuke|last2=1926-2010.|first2=\u5347\u5473\u6e96\u4e4b\u8f14|date=1985|publisher=T\u014dky\u014d Daigaku Shuppankai|isbn=978-4130330268|edition=Shohan|location=T\u014dky\u014d|oclc=15423787}}</ref> The years of Japan under 1955 regime witnessed the [[Japanese economic miracle|economic miracle]], but also the dominance of the ruling party in the [[National Diet|Diet]], with an undergirded tight connection between the bureaucracy and the business sector. Due to a series of LDP scandals and the 1992 burst of [[Japanese asset price bubble]], LDP lost its majority in the [[House of Representatives of Japan|House of Representatives]] in the [[1993 Japanese general election|1993 general election]].\n\n''<nowiki/>''\n\n''<nowiki/>''\n\n''<nowiki/>''\n\n== Background ==\n\n=== Pre-1955 Multiparty System ===\n[[File:Japanese_General_election,_1947_en.svg|alt=|thumb|250x250px|House of Representatives Seat Distribution in 1947]]\nAfter World War II, Japan was controlled by the [[Supreme Commander for the Allied Powers]] (SCAP). SCAP aimed at the eradication of militarism and the promotion of democratization in Japan, and therefore it issues a series of policies to arrest suspected war criminals which shuffled the political power in Japan.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite book|title=Politics in modern Japan : development and organization|last=1928-|first=Kishimoto, K\u014dichi|date=1997|publisher=Japan Echo|isbn=978-4915226076|location=|pages=21\u201323|oclc=38224699}}</ref> Power of parties on the right side of the political spectrum lost declined in the immediate post war periods due to the purge. The [[Japan Progressive Party]] lost about 90% of the seats in the purge, while the [[Liberal Party (Japan, 1950)|Japan Liberal Party]] lost about 45%. Meanwhile, since many parties on the left were only legalized under the command of SCAP after the WW2, they were barely influenced by the purge.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|title=The making of modern Japan|last=B.|first=Jansen, Marius|date=2000|publisher=Belknap Press of Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0674003347|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/makingofmodernja00jans/page/675 675]|oclc=44090600|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/makingofmodernja00jans/page/675}}</ref> As a result, the [[Socialist Party of Japan|Socialist Party]] ''(\u65e5\u672c\u793e\u4f1a\u515a)'' led by [[Tetsu Katayama]] ''(\u7247\u5c71\u54f2)'' won the [[1947 Japanese general election|first general election]] after the enforcement of the constitution of Japan.\n\nAlthough at the time no formal regulations about how to form a coalition government existed, there was a consensus among the major parties that a coalition government should be formed to manage the post-war economic problems. Nonetheless, which party would be included in the coalition took a long process of negotiations. Both a four-party coalition excluding the Communist Party and a three-party coalition excluding both the [[Japanese Communist Party|Communist Party]] and the Liberal Party were suggested within the socialists. The Liberal party, led by anticommunist [[Shigeru Yoshida]] ''(\u5409\u7530\u8302)'', showed great reluctance of joining the coalition.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|title=Japan's postwar party politics|last=1962-|first=Kohno, Masaru|date=1997|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0691026299|location=|pages=50\u201353|oclc=441854586}}</ref> At a meeting between the Katayama and Yoshida in May 19, 1947, the Liberal Party asked Katayama to \u201cbreak off with the leftists\u201d in return of its participation in the coalition. Since the Socialist Party had already claimed to officially cut ties with the Communist Party earlier, it refused such demand.<ref name=\":62\">{{Cite book|title=\u4e94\u4e94\u5e74\u4f53\u5236\u3068\u65e5\u672c\u793e\u4f1a\u515a|last=\u6881\u7530|first=\u6d69\u797a|publisher=\u3042\u308a\u3048\u3059\u66f8\u623f|year=1981|isbn=|location=\u6771\u4eac|pages=81\u201384}}</ref> The lengthy coalition-building process ended up with a government headed by the Socialist Party, the Democratic Party, and the [[National Cooperative Party]].<ref name=\":42\" />\n\nThe Katayama-led coalition government did not last more than a year due to opposition from both inside the Socialist Party and outside. In order to form a coalition, Katayama had to make concessions which departed from original policy proposals, which further facilitated the split between the leftist faction and the rightist faction within the party. At the same time, policies which Katayama did implement, such as nationalization of coal and mine production, drove the conservatives away.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n=== Yoshida Hegemony ===\n[[File:Japanese_General_election,_1949_en.svg|thumb|246x246px|House of Representatives Seat Distribution in 1949]]\nAfter the failure of Katayama cabinet, voters lost confidence in the Socialist Party, which led to the takeover of government by Yoshida Shigeru. In the [[1949 Japanese general election|general election of 1949]], the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Japan)|Democratic Liberal Party]] led by Yoshida won a majority in the House of representatives with 269 seats out of 466 seats, while the Socialist Party won only 48 seats. This was the first majority cabinet in post-war Japan.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Postwar Japan : 1945 to the present|last=J.|first=Bayley, Paul|date=1996|publisher=Blackwell|isbn=978-0631179016|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/postwarjapan19450000bail/page/58 58]|oclc=807111830|url=https://archive.org/details/postwarjapan19450000bail/page/58}}</ref>\n\nYoshida Shigeru organized five cabinets as a prime minister between 1946 to 1954. The diplomatic, economic, and security policies which Yoshida adopted when he was in power were altogether referred as the \u201c[[Yoshida Doctrine]]\u201d.<ref name=\":72\">{{Cite journal|last=Sugita|first=Yoneyuki|date=2016|title=The Yoshida Doctrine as a Myth|url=http://www.jaas.gr.jp/jjas/pdf/2016/06_SUGIYAMA.pdf|journal=The Japanese Journal of American Studies|volume=27|pages=|via=}}</ref> These policies remained influential even after him being voted out of the office by a no-confidence motion by the \u201cYoshida students\u201d who followed his ideology.<ref name=\":02\" /> The Yoshida Doctrine has three major components: 1. Japan relies on its alliance with the U.S. for national security; 2. Japan preserves a low level of self-defense capacity; 3. Japan should concentrate on the reconstruction of domestic economy.<ref name=\":72\" /> The Yoshida Doctrine set the tone for Japan\u2019s economic miracle and alignment with the West. However, Yoshida\u2019s \u201cone man\u201d leadership and anti-communist stance was criticized and eventually led to the defection of many Diet members from his party to the new [[Democratic Party (Japan, 1954)|Democratic Party]], causing his cabinet to resign on December 7, 1954.<ref name=\":52\" />\n\n=== Fall of Yoshida Shigeru ===\n[[File:Brawling_diet_2.JPG|thumb|227x227px|Dietmembers brawl due to the steamrolling of the amendment to the Police Act.]]\nThe criticisms of Yoshida cabinet mainly focused on three issues:\n\n# In 1951, The [[Treaty of San Francisco|San Francisco Peace Treaty]] and the [[Security Treaty Between the United States and Japan]] was signed under Yoshida cabinet. The Peace Treaty was signed without the communist bloc\u2019s presence, which was condemned by the Communist Party for its anti-communist stance. The Security Treaty was criticized by both the Communist Party and the Socialist Party for the risk of remilitarization, while also criticized by the conservatives for putting Japan in a subordinate position, since Japan was asked to provide military base for the U.S.\u2019s force.<ref name=\":82\">{{Cite book|title=\u6226\u5f8c\u6539\u9769\u3068\u9006\u30b3\u30fc\u30b9|last=\u5409\u7530|first=\u88d5|publisher=\u5409\u5ddd\u5f18\u6587\u9928|year=2004|isbn=|location=\u6771\u4eac|pages=81\u201385}}</ref>\n# During the fifth Yoshida cabinet, several bills were passed with the strong opposition of the Leftist Socialist Party of Japan and the Rightist Socialist Party of Japan, including the Strike Control Act, the Mutual Defense Assistance Agreement between Japan and the United States of America, two education acts which restrict the political participation of school teachers, amendment to the Police Act, Self-Defense Forces Act. Among which, the amendment to the Police Act was steamrolled with the opposition parties absent from the Diet.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=\u4e94\u4e94\u5e74\u4f53\u5236\u3068\u5b89\u4fdd\u95d8\u4e89|last=\u6b74\u53f2\u5b66\u7814\u7a76\u4f1a|publisher=\u9752\u6728\u66f8\u5e97|year=1990|isbn=|location=\u6771\u4eac|pages=82}}</ref>\n# The Yoshida cabinet was also involved in two major corruption cases. One is known as the Hozen Keizai Kai Incident ''(\u4fdd\u5168\u7d4c\u6e08\u4f1a\u4e8b\u4ef6)''. Masutomi Ito, the director of a financial institution Hozen Keizai Kai which, was accused of fraud and suspected of making political bribery, which resulted in the arrests of several conservative politicians.<ref name=\":22\" /> The other is known as the Shipbuilding Bribery ''(\u9020\u8239\u7591\u7344)'', in which the shipping business and shipbuilding business were proved to be making pay-off to conservative politicians. Influential politicians in the ruling party such as [[Eisaku Sat\u014d|Eisaku Sato]] ''(\u4f50\u85e4\u6804\u4f5c)'' and [[Hayato Ikeda]] ''(\u6c60\u7530\u52c7\u4eba)'' were suspected as bribe takers. The Yoshida cabinet reacted to this incident by stopping the arrest of Eisaku Sato.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://showa.mainichi.jp/news/1954/04/post-1e45.html|title=\u9020\u8239\u7591\u7344\u3067\u6307\u63ee\u6a29\u767a\u52d5|last=|first=|date=21 April 1954|work=\u6bce\u65e5\u65b0\u805e|access-date=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe three controversies led to the gathering of anti-Yoshida forces. On October 20, 1954, anti-Yoshida conservatives formed a coalition party: the [[Democratic Party (Japan, 1954)|Japan Democratic Party]] ''(\u65e5\u672c\u6c11\u4e3b\u515a)''. The Japan Democratic Party along with the Leftist Socialist Party of Japan and the Rightist Socialist Party of Japan tabled a [[Motion of no confidence|no-confidence motion]] against the cabinet on December 6 and won the majority. As a result, Yoshida Cabinet resigned on December 7 after six years of rule.\n\n== Establishment of the 1955 System ==\n\n=== Merger of the Japan Socialist Party (JSP) ===\nWithin the Socialist party, ideological conflicts had long been a problem. The leftists in the party adopted a Marx-Lenin ideology as China, while the rightists leaned towards a socialist welfare nation under a capitalist system. The San Francisco Peace Treaty and the Security Treaty Between the United States and Japan signed in 1951 triggered the final split. The right socialists agreed on the San Francisco Peace Treaty but were against the Security Treaty, due to their constitutionalist stance, while the left socialists were against both treaties due to their exclusion of Soviet Union.<ref name=\":02\" /> On October 23, 1951, the old Socialist Party officially split into the [[Leftist Socialist Party of Japan]] ''(\u5de6\u6d3e\u793e\u4f1a\u515a)'' and the [[Rightist Socialist Party of Japan]] ''(\u53f3\u6d3e\u793e\u4f1a\u515a)''.\n\nAfter the split, however, the socialists soon realized the necessity of merging into one party to fight against the anti-communist approach taken by the GHQ and the conservatives, which is commonly referred to as the [[Reverse Course|reverse course]] ''(\u9006\u30b3\u30fc\u30b9)''. After the San Francisco Peace Treaty came into effect, influential members from the Rightist Socialist Party of Japan came back from the purge and boosted the power of the rightists. The Leftist Socialist Party of Japan also expanded its power with the support of the [[General Council of Trade Unions of Japan]], also known as ''Sohyo(\u65e5\u672c\u52b4\u50cd\u7d44\u5408\u7dcf\u8a55\u8b70\u4f1a)''. Meanwhile, the conservatives were suffering criticisms from the public for the corruption scandals and Security Treaty. Sensing the possibility of success, despite their ideological differences, to take power from the political right and fight against the anti-communist movement, the socialists decided to reunite and formed the Japan Socialist Party (JSP) on October 13, 1955.<ref name=\":62\" />\n[[File:Japanese_General_election,_1955_en.svg|left|thumb|257x257px|Before the merger: House of Representative Seat Distribution in 1955]]\nOne crucial external factor that caused the merger of JSD is ''Sohyo''. ''Sohyo'', the abbreviation of the General Council of Trade Unions of Japan, was a trade confederation in Japan which was established on July 11, 1950, soon after the start of the Korean War. It incorporated about 48% of organized workers in Japan. Initially, ''Sohyo''was the unified body of anti-communist unions, but it soon changed from a centralist stance to a left stance due to the remilitarization tendency of Japan shown in the Korean War.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Incorporating Japanese labor into the Free World: Cold War diplomacy and economic interdependence, 1949\u20131964|journal = Labor History|volume = 49|issue = 2|pages = 199\u2013222|last=Nakakita|first=Koji|date=2008|doi=10.1080/00236560801950972}}</ref> Due to the rationalization strategy taken by the conservative government, Japanese workers, particular those worked in small and median-sized factories were facing slow wage increase and even dismissals. In response, ''Sohyo'' organized the anti-rationalization campaign and pressured the merger of JSP.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Disparaged success : labor politics in postwar Japan|last=1957-|first=Kume, Ikuo|date=1998|publisher=Cornell Univ. Press|isbn=978-0801433641|oclc=833127781|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/disparagedsucces0000kume}}</ref>\n[[File:Japanese_General_election,_1958_en.svg|left|thumb|257x257px|After the merger: House of Representatives Seat Distribution in 1958]]\n\n=== Merger of the Liberal Democratic Party of Japan (LDP) ===\nIn the [[1955 Japanese general election|1955 general election]], the conservative Japan Democratic Party won the ruling position. Meanwhile, the Leftist Socialist Party of Japan was able to win 17 more seats. The expansion of Leftist Socialist Party of Japan and the soon formation of the leftists and rightists in the socialist camp into JSP became a more substantial threat for the conservatives. As a result, also in 1955, the Japan Democratic Party and the Japan Liberal Party merged as Liberal Democratic Party of Japan (LDP).<ref name=\":82\" />\n\nThe expansion of the socialist power also worried the ''Zaikai''(business community). ''Zaikai'' had incentives to secure a conservative government since it would pump money into the big companies to keep their competitiveness, stay in a close relationship with the U.S. to maintain a liberal trade policy, and deal with the intensified anti-rationalization labor movement. Therefore, to counter the socialist power, the ''Zaikai'' pressured the Liberal Party and the Democratic Party to merge.<ref name=\":92\">{{Cite journal|last=Masumi|first=Junnosuke|date=1988|title=The 1955 System in Japan and Its Subsequent Development|journal=Asian Survey|volume=28|issue=3|pages=286\u2013306|doi=10.1525/as.1988.28.3.01p0146p|issn=0004-4687|url=http://as.ucpress.edu/content/ucpas/28/3/286.full.pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Outcome of the merger: 1955 System ===\nAfter the formation of the two major parties, JSP and LDP, a [[1958 Japanese general election|general election]] was held in 1958. Although the Socialist Party was gaining more power at the time, the conservative Liberal Party and Democratic Party had more voters from the beginning, not to mention after the merge of the two. As a result, the LDP won almost as twice as many seats as JSP. The 1955 system, also known as \u201cone and a half system\u201d, was established, in which LDP always as the dominant party and JSP never able to be a strong enough alternative.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|title=The politics of electoral systems|date=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Gallagher, Michael, 1951-, Mitchell, Paul, 1964-|isbn=9780191531514|location=Oxford|oclc=68623713}}</ref>\n\n1955 system essentially was the symbol of the two parties\u2019 confrontation over two major issues: the [[Constitution of Japan|1946 constitution]] and the security treaty.<ref name=\":92\" /> During the occupation years, Minister Matsumoto Joji ''(\u677e\u672c\u70dd\u6cbb)'' drafted the 1946 constitution under the demand of General [[Douglas MacArthur]]. Unsatisfied with the draft, the draft was later then revised by the SCAP. Therefore, the 1946 constitution was more of American authorship and the banner for SCAP\u2019s goal of democratization of Japan. The conservative parties had the consideration of constitution revision since its enactment. Although varying in extent, the revision of [[Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution|Article 9]] to permit a rearmament program had been widely argued with the conservative parties since the Yoshida cabinet. At the same time, the socialist parties opposed any revision of the constitution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ward|first=Robert E.|date=1956|title=The Constitution and Current Japanese Politics|journal=Far Eastern Survey|volume=25|issue=4|pages=49\u201358|doi=10.2307/3023907|issn=0362-8949|jstor=3023907}}</ref>\n\nAnother issue was the security Treaty signed in 1951, a product of the late occupation years. Different from the 1946 constitution which aims at wiping out the [[Japanese militarism|militarism in Japan]], the Security Treaty was the consequence of U.S. securing its military strength in Asia to counter the communist threat in the [[Cold War]]. JSP strongly opposed the Security Treaty due to the underlying possibility of further rearmament and even revival militarism in Japan, while LDP argued that the presence of the U.S. army in Japan was merely for self-defense.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Protest in tokyo - the security treaty crisis of 1960.|last=R.|first=Packard, George|year=|isbn=9780691650746|location=|pages=3\u201322|oclc=1023228016}}</ref>\n\n== LDP dominance in the 1955 system ==\n\n=== Electoral system ===\nThe electoral system that was used under 1955 system is known as the [[Single non-transferable vote|Single Nontransferable Vote]] (SNTV). Under SNTV, each constituency has multiple seats to be filled. Voters instead of voting for parties, votes for individual candidates, and seats of the constituency go to whoever wins the most votes. One problem of such electoral system is that the fair allocation of seats to different parties are not taken into consideration: Since the winners of most votes eventually get the seats, candidates of one party can take all the seats of one constituency.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nUnder such electoral system, LDP with its massive political donation put other opposition parties into disadvantage. Due to LDP\u2019s ties with big companies, the party directed the financial resources to individual candidates and enabled them to promise patronage to their voters, with a focus on the agricultural population, while the reallocation of Diet seats did not keep up with the migration from rural to urban area due to industrialization. Aside from the pork-barrel spending, the LDP candidates also cultivated personalism through [[Koenkai]] ''(\u5f8c\u63f4\u4f1a)'' in their own constituency. Politicians went to the locals\u2019 wedding, funeral, birthday parties and so on. In such occasions, politicians often brought considerable amount of cash gift. Candidates would even organize activities such as hot springs for their supporters.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOn the account of its self-assertiveness, LDP unilaterally altered the rules for campaigning. Profiting of its constituted koenkai canvas, the competition rules were toughened for the Opposition. The formal campaign periods were short (and shortened further over time), television and radio advertising being prohibited and low limits placed on posters and handbills. Through the campaign, however, each candidate was granted two five-minute slots on television when a stream of candidates would line up and take turns in front of a stationary microphone to run through their list of promises right after which the next candidate would take other. Such rules of play were discouraging and difficult for a would-be challenger while LDP benefitted from the unfair restraints of participation by the sheer amount of runners.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Japanese party system : from one-party rule to coalition government|last=1945-|first=Hrebenar, Ronald J.|date=1986|publisher=Westview Press|others=Berton, Peter, 1922-2014.|isbn=978-0813303468|location=Boulder, Colo.|oclc=13455801}}</ref>\n\nAnother neglected flaw of the electoral system which bolstered LDP's dominance was the urgent need for redistricting in the wake of the post-war rapid population shifts from the rural to urban areas. The swelling urban populations were much trickier for LDP politicians to fit within the distributed koenkai grassroot structure as they were more peripatetic and atomized than the traditional rural household. These voters had new policy demands (ex. issues related to [[Environmental issues in Japan#Environment deterioration in the 1960s|environmental deterioration in the 1960s]]) which conflicted with the ones practiced by LDP for their industry and big-business support. Under the obsolete district constituencies, the farmers retained disproportionate political influence which as a consequence of pork-barrel desires rather than by concern over issues of broad social policy, stagnated democratic alternation.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite book|title=Japan transformed : political change and economic restructuring|last=McCall.|first=Rosenbluth, Frances |author-link=Frances McCall Rosenbluth|date=2010|publisher=Princeton University Press|others=Thies, Michael F.|isbn=9780691135915|location=Princeton, N.J.|oclc=428926469}}</ref>\n\nUnder the current electoral rules, LDP was motivated to develop loyal personal support for the farmer's voter group. Being a nationally organized group of voters and united around the single issue of agricultural protectionism, the party could tune higher import tariffs and subsidies to support the less productive small businesses which because of their large numbers, could turn out at elections and vote in predictable ways.\n\n=== Bureaucratization of policymaking ===\nSince the institution of the 1955 system, the legislative independence has been declining in the face of a growth in the combined legislative power of the bureaucracy and the ruling conservative party. Indicators that point to this are the success rates of governmental and individual member bills; the declining rate of amendments added; and the singular lack of success for opposition-sponsored bills. For example, the mere submission of nongovernmentally sponsored measures is extremely difficult. In the [[House of Representatives (Japan)|Lower House]], at least 20 representatives must support a \"member\" bill before it can be introduced, while in the [[House of Councillors (Japan)|Upper House]] ten supporters are required. Moreover, should the bill require the expenditure of state funds, fifty and twenty supporters respectively are necessary.\n\nThe chance for success of bureaucratic bills that was only 1.3 times greater than that for individual Diet-generated bills under the [[Occupation of Japan|Occupation]] and about twice as great from 1952 to 1955, it augmented to 7 times greater by 1974, when approximately 90% of all successful legislation has been cabinet-sponsored.<ref name=\":102\">{{Cite journal|last=Pempel|first=T. J.|date=November 1974|title=The Bureaucratization of Policymaking in Postwar Japan|journal=American Journal of Political Science|volume=18|issue=4|pages=647\u2013664|doi=10.2307/2110551|issn=0092-5853|jstor=2110551}}</ref> In addition, the Diet has not been notably active as a potential amender for which there are two devices open: it can either \"amend\" (''shusei''), or it can \"add supplementary resolution of clarification\" (''futai ketsugi''). From 1955 to 1960 just over one-third of all successful government legislation went through one or another of these processes. In the 48th Diet (1964-1965) this rate was 17% and in the 63rd Diet (1970) it was 15%. Finally, opposition bills had no chance of success: of 317 opposition bills introduced from the 37th (1960) through the 46th (1963-1964) Diets, not one became law.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Misawa|first=Shigeo|date=1967-05-30|journal=The Annuals of Japanese Political Science Association|volume=18|pages=5\u201333, 2|doi=10.7218/nenpouseijigaku1953.18.0_5|issn=0549-4192|title=Outline of Policy-Decision Making Process Since 1955|doi-access=free}}</ref> These numbers attest that by the time bills materialize in the Diet a general agreement has already been reached, both within and between the bureaucracy and the LDP. In such an environment, opposition and the generation of successful alternatives from within the Diet itself has become extremely difficult.<ref name=\":102\" />\n\nBesides, the bureaucracy wields considerable and increasing power through the use of nonlegislative devices such a subordinances and communications, and through its varying degrees of dominance over technical and nonpartisan advisory groups.<ref name=\":102\" />\n\n=== Policy decision-making ===\nThe [[Policy Affairs Research Council]] (\u653f\u52d9\u8abf\u67fb\u4f1a ''seimu ch\u014dsakai'') or \"PARC\" was the major policymaking body within the LDP. Its members were the LDP representatives in both legislative houses, and it was the basic forum in which the party discussed and negotiated government policy. The policymaking under this system did not comply with the usual model of a parliamentary cabinet government which involves strong cabinet leadership and coordination. Instead, representatives who were not in the cabinet were often the other pivot of policy through their formal roles PARC. In consultation with bureaucrats and interest groups, the council already had input into policy before the cabinet and prime minister or upper party executives could shape it further. At its height in the mid-1980s, PARC had as many as seventeen divisions.\n\n==== Industrial policy ====\nJapan's industrial policy under the 1955 system was undergirded by a political logic that supports firms and whole industries that would not have been sustainable in a less-regulated economy, imposed high prices and taxes, limited choice in the marketplace, and rigid career paths.<ref name=\":32\" /> In spite of the fact that Japan came out of war with a theoretical comparative advantage towards light manufacturing which would match its profile of low-capital, abundant-labor economy, the war skewed its economic profile toward heavy industries. The large war companies lobbied for a development strategy favoring heavy industry and received subsidies and regulatory favoritism. In exchange, LDP members were awarded with campaign contributions to be able to stay electorally competitive against each other in the multi-member districts.\n\nThe Heavy Industries Bureau of the [[Ministry of International Trade and Industry]] assisted the heavy industries with policies such as:\n\n* Limiting entry and often regulating the market pricing to help stabilize profits.\n* Privileging access to cheap loans from the Japan Development Bank\n* Domestic government budget subsidies and tax breaks as well as favored access to foreign exchange and tariff protections.\n\nSuch strategy of developmental policy which has strong state involvement in developmental orientation is typical of late industrialing countries and in terms of [[international political economy]], follows the model of the [[developmental state]]. Explicit implication implies a degree of corruption, which during [[Kakuei Tanaka]]'s office in 1971-1972 resulted in media noticing corruption which, in one instance, resulted in the [[Kakuei Tanaka#Lockheed scandal and aftermath|Lockheed scandal]].\n\n== The fall of the system ==\n\n=== Global Pressure and the Collapse of Bubble Economy ===\nAs a corollary of the [[Plaza Accord|Plaza Accord of 1985]] when Japan agreed to allow substantial appreciation of the yen, the Japanese government reduced the interests marginally above the rate of inflation as a domestic relief strategy. This resulted in banks and corporations going on an enormous spending spree with nearly free money, bidding up the price of real estate and other assets.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Unwanted company : foreign investment in American industries|last=1965-|first=Crystal, Jonathan|isbn=9781501723612|location=Ithaca|oclc=1042219263}}</ref>\n\nAgainst the faith of many people that Japan would come to dominate the world economy, the [[Japanese asset price bubble]] led to a bubble crash after the raising of interest rates of the [[Bank of Japan]] in 1990 and firms together with their jobs were in mortal danger. In this context and on the background of LDP's short-term relieved pressure from the already shaky electoral coalition between exporters and the non-traded sectors, the voting public expressed disenchantment toward the ruling Liberal Democratic Party.\n\nThe new electoral system following the [[1994 Japanese electoral reform|1994 Electoral reform]] which was claimed to reduce corruption and high elections costs, promote more policy debates, and encourage a two-party system. As a consequence of this reform as well as the change of voter behavior and the change of the international environment, the system collapsed completely following the [[2005 Japanese general election|2005]] and [[2009 Japanese general election|2009]] general elections which demonstrated significant shifts in both the foundations of party support and the importance of national swings in support for one party or another. Since 2005, urban-rural differences in the foundations of the leading parties have changed dramatically, and Japan has moved from a system dominated by locally based, individual candidacies toward a two-party system in which both party popularity and personal characteristics influence electoral success or failure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thies|first=Michael F.|last2=Scheiner|first2=Ethan|last3=Reed|first3=Steven R.|date=2012-07-14|title=The End of LDP Dominance and the Rise of Party-Oriented Politics in Japan|journal=The Journal of Japanese Studies|volume=38|issue=2|pages=353\u2013376|doi=10.1353/jjs.2012.0037|issn=1549-4721}}</ref>\n\nThe specialist on theoretical knowledge of legislative institutions and electoral systems, Michael Thies, argues that majoritarian institutions of the Anglo-American variety would have pushed politics toward broader coalitions, reducing the premiums captured by organized groups with extreme preferences, and appealing more to the interests of unorganized, diverse voters. A study on the representation of unorganized groups under [[proportional representation]] (featuring multi-member [[Electoral district|voting-districts]]) concludes that closed-list proportional representation makes legislators generally more responsive to interest groups and less responsive to unorganized voters than single-member districts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thies|first=Michael F.|last2=Bawn|first2=Kathleen|date=2003|title=A Comparative Theory of Electoral Incentives: Representing the Unorganized Under PR, Plurality, and Mixed-Member Electoral Systems.|location=Rochester, NY|doi=10.2139/ssrn.1158628|ssrn=1158628}}</ref> An even representation would have given labor a persistent and politically potent voice of the kind seen in continental Europe.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[1947 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1949 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1955 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1958 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1993 Japanese general election]]\n* [[1994 Japanese electoral reform|1994 Electoral reform]]\n* [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]]\n* [[Social Democratic Party (Japan)|Social Democratic Party]]\n* [[Japanese economic miracle]]\n* [[Zaibatsu]]\n* [[Government-business relations in Japan]]\n* [[Kakuei Tanaka|Tanaka Kakuei]]\n* [[Koenkai]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Politics of Post-war Japan]]\n[[Category:Cold War history of Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Pjodct", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePre-1955 Multiparty System", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1955_System"}
{"title_page": "U.S. Route 202", "text_new": "{{short description|Highway in the United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=USA\n|type=US\n|route=202\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|frame-lat=42.233975|frame-long=-72.19149|zoom=5|type=line|from=U.S. Route 202.map}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=US&nbsp;202 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=629.6\n|established=1935\n|direction_a=South<!--US 202 signed north-south at its Delaware terminus-->\n|direction_b=East<!--US 202 signed east-west at its Maine terminus-->\n|terminus_a={{Jct|country=USA|US|13|US|40}} in [[New Castle, Delaware|New Castle, DE]]\n|junction=<!--MAJOR JUNCTIONS ONLY-->{{plainlist|\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|95}} from [[Newport, Delaware|Newport]] to [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington, DE]]\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|76|dab1=east}} in [[King of Prussia, Pennsylvania|King of Prussia, PA]]\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|287}} in [[Bridgewater, New Jersey|Bridgewater, NJ]]\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|80}} in [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany, NJ]]\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|84|dab1=east|US|6}} in [[Brewster, NY]] and [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury, CT]]\n*{{Jct|state=MA|I|90|MATP}} in [[Westfield, Massachusetts|Westfield, MA]]\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|91|US|5}} in [[Holyoke, Massachusetts|Holyoke, MA]]\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|89}} in [[Hopkinton, New Hampshire|Hopkinton, NH]]\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|93|I|393|US|4}} in [[Concord, New Hampshire|Concord, NH]]\n*{{Jct|country=USA|I|95}} in [[Augusta, Maine|Augusta, ME]]\n}}\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=ME|US-Bus|1A|US|2|dab1=Bangor}} in [[Bangor, Maine|Bangor, ME]]\n|states=[[Delaware]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Connecticut]], [[Massachusetts]], [[New Hampshire]], [[Maine]]\n|spur_type=US\n|spur_of=2\n}}\n'''U.S. Route&nbsp;202''' ('''US&nbsp;202''') is a spur route of [[U.S. Route 2]]. It follows a northeasterly and southwesterly direction stretching from [[Delaware]] to [[Maine]], also traveling through the states of [[Pennsylvania]], [[New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Connecticut]], [[Massachusetts]], and [[New Hampshire]]. The highway has borne the number 202 since at least 1936.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/infrastructure/us202.cfm |title=U.S.&nbsp;202 - Maine to Delaware - General Highway History |publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]] |website=www.fhwa.dot.gov |language=en |access-date=June 2, 2018 }}</ref> Before this, sections of the highway were designated U.S.&nbsp;Route&nbsp;122,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18462454/route_122_north_has_been_changed_to_202/ |title=Route&nbsp;122 North Has Been Changed to 202 |newspaper=[[The News Journal]] |location=[[Wilmington, Delaware]] |page=16 |date=March 15, 1935 |access-date=March 20, 2018 |via=newspapers.com }}</ref> as it intersected [[U.S. Route 22|US&nbsp;22]]. Its current designation is based on its intersection with [[U.S. Route 2|US&nbsp;2]] in Maine.\n\nThis highway is considerably longer than the eastern segment of US&nbsp;2, making it one of several three-digit U.S. highways to be longer than their parent routes.\n\n==Route description==\n{{lengths table|length_ref=<ref name=\"NHDOT Roads\">{{cite web|url=http://www.granit.unh.edu/data/search?dset=roads_dot|title=NH Public Roads|author=Bureau of Planning & Community Assistance|date=February 20, 2015|website=|publisher=[[New Hampshire Department of Transportation]]|place=Concord, New Hampshire|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|[[U.S. Route 202 in Delaware|DE]]\n|{{convert|13.06|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[U.S. Route 202 in Pennsylvania|PA]]\n|{{convert|59.002|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[U.S. Route 202 in New Jersey|NJ]]\n|{{convert|80.31|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[U.S. Route 202 in New York|NY]]\n|{{convert|55.57|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[U.S. Route 202 in Connecticut|CT]]\n|{{convert|75.14|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[U.S. Route 202 in Massachusetts|MA]]\n|{{convert|79.6|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[U.S. Route 202 in New Hampshire|NH]]\n|{{convert|95.270|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[U.S. Route 202 in Maine|ME]]\n|{{convert|170.3|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|Total\n|{{convert|628.252|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|}\n\n===Delaware===\n{{main|U.S. Route 202 in Delaware}}\nUS&nbsp;202 begins at an interchange with [[U.S. Route 13 (Delaware)|US&nbsp;13]]/[[U.S. Route 40 in Delaware|US&nbsp;40]] south of [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]]. It runs north along the same road as [[Delaware Route 141]], then joins with [[Interstate 95 in Delaware|Interstate 95]] through Wilmington. North of the city, it exits the freeway onto Concord Pike, heading north; [[Delaware Route 202]] also continues south from this point. US&nbsp;202 continues north towards the state line as a six-lane [[arterial road]] and is lined with numerous strip malls and \"[[big-box stores]]\".\n\n===Pennsylvania===\n{{main|U.S. Route 202 in Pennsylvania}}\n[[File:US 202 NB shield between PA 463 and County Line Road.jpeg|thumb|right|US 202 parkway northbound in Montgomery Township, PA]]\nUS&nbsp;202 continues north toward [[West Chester, Pennsylvania|West Chester]], joining with [[U.S. Route 322|US&nbsp;322]] after intersecting [[U.S. Route 1]]. South of [[West Chester, Pennsylvania|West Chester]], US&nbsp;202/322 exits onto a limited-access bypass of the borough; that is the old West Chester By-Pass, and includes a grade-level intersection at Matlack Street. North of West Chester, US&nbsp;322 exits, and US&nbsp;202 continues north as a freeway towards [[Frazer, Pennsylvania|Frazer]], where it interchanges with [[U.S. Route 30]] and bends east to head towards [[Malvern, Pennsylvania|Malvern]] and [[King of Prussia, Pennsylvania|King of Prussia]]. The stretch between Mill Lane in Malvern to King of Prussia was recently widened to three lanes in each direction.  In King of Prussia, the highway forms a large, complicated interchange with the [[Schuylkill Expressway]], the [[Pennsylvania Turnpike]], and [[U.S. Route 422]].\n\nThe freeway then transitions into a [[divided highway]], passing the [[King of Prussia (mall)|King of Prussia]] mall and heading northeast through commercial areas before splitting into a [[one-way pair]] through the streets of [[Bridgeport, Pennsylvania|Bridgeport]] and [[Norristown, Pennsylvania|Norristown]], crossing the [[Schuylkill River]] in the process.\n\nNorth of Norristown, US&nbsp;202 continues as a two-lane road heading northeast through the Philadelphia suburbs, passing through [[Blue Bell, Pennsylvania|Blue Bell]] and [[Lower Gwynedd Township, Pennsylvania|Lower Gwynedd]], where it becomes a four-lane full-access highway for about two miles (3&nbsp;km). East of [[Lansdale, Pennsylvania|Lansdale]], in [[Montgomeryville, Pennsylvania|Montgomeryville]], it turns into a parkway with a [[US 202 Parkway Trail|parallel trail]], which opened in December 2012.<ref name=intell12312>{{cite news|first=Freda R.|last=Savana|title=It's official: The 202 parkway is open|work=[[The Intelligencer (Doylestown, Pennsylvania)|The Intelligencer]]|date=December 3, 2012|url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/my_town/doylestown/it-s-official-the-parkway-is-open/article_494036d4-0b7b-5e49-8ac6-b706709c40ac.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130131090403/http://www.phillyburbs.com/my_town/doylestown/it-s-official-the-parkway-is-open/article_494036d4-0b7b-5e49-8ac6-b706709c40ac.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 31, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2012}}</ref> It continues northeast towards [[Doylestown, Pennsylvania|Doylestown]], where it joins an older section of bypass at [[Pennsylvania Route 611]] and proceeds north to the old alignment of Route 202 (State Street). It continues as a two-lane road to [[New Hope, Pennsylvania|New Hope]], crossing the [[Delaware River]] on the [[New Hope-Lambertville Toll Bridge]].\n\n===New Jersey===\n{{main|U.S. Route 202 in New Jersey}}\nOn the toll bridge, US&nbsp;202 has two lanes in each direction. It continues a northeasterly course for about {{convert|5.7|mi|km}} as a [[freeway]]. This segment of US&nbsp;202 was earlier called the US&nbsp;202 bypass (as it bypassed the [[New Hope, Pennsylvania|New Hope]]-[[Lambertville, New Jersey|Lambertville]] area) from its original route. The old section of US&nbsp;202 between New Hope and [[Ringoes, New Jersey]] is now [[New Jersey Route 179|Route&nbsp;179]] which is also [[Old York Road]], the first roadway to connect [[New York City]] and [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].  In 1953, this section of Old York Road was renumbered US&nbsp;202.  A small section of the US&nbsp;202 bypass was built in 1965 and the old route was renamed Route&nbsp;179.  When the western section of the bypass was built to the Delaware River, the whole former segment was renamed Route&nbsp;179. The section of the new US&nbsp;202 freeway section ends once it begins to run concurrently with [[New Jersey Route 31|Route&nbsp;31]] in [[East Amwell Township, New Jersey|East Amwell Township]]. The concurrency runs for five miles (8&nbsp;km), to [[Flemington, New Jersey|Flemington]].  This stretch, and the 13 miles (21&nbsp;km) between Flemington and [[Somerville, New Jersey|Somerville]], is a four-lane divided roadway.\n\n[[Image:US202NYNJborder.jpg|thumb|US&nbsp;202 just inside New Jersey at the NY/NJ state line]]\nAt Somerville, the road merges with [[U.S. Route 206|US&nbsp;206]] at a now-reconfigured [[Somerville Circle]].  Parts of the old [[traffic circle]], which also carries [[New Jersey Route 28|Route&nbsp;28]], remain below the US&nbsp;202 [[Overpass|flyover]].  US&nbsp;202 splits northeastward from US&nbsp;206 at [[Bedminster Township, New Jersey|Bedminster Township]] and again becomes a two-lane road.\n\nFrom here to the state line, US&nbsp;202 parallels, and has largely been supplanted by, [[Interstate 287|I-287]], which during its construction dumped traffic onto US&nbsp;202. US&nbsp;202 continues through [[Morristown, New Jersey|Morristown]] to [[Morris Plains, New Jersey|Morris Plains]] with an intersection with [[New Jersey Route 53|Route&nbsp;53]]. With a few exceptions, US&nbsp;202 is maintained by counties rather than the [[New Jersey Department of Transportation]] north of Route&nbsp;53.\n\nThe following sections are state-maintained:\n*At the [[Interstate 80 in New Jersey|I-80]] interchange\n*At the [[U.S. Route 46|US&nbsp;46]] intersection\n*Along the [[New Jersey Route 23|Route&nbsp;23]] concurrency\n*At the [[Interstate 287|I-287]] interchange in [[Oakland, New Jersey|Oakland]]\n\nUS&nbsp;202 continues past [[Boonton, New Jersey|Boonton]] along the [[Boonton Turnpike]] to historic Mountain View in [[Wayne, New Jersey|Wayne]], where it then picks up Route&nbsp;23 for about two miles (3&nbsp;km) and then exits on Black Oak Ridge Road.  It then follows the [[Paterson-Hamburg Turnpike]], Terhune Drive on the east side of Pompton Lake (past the former homes of Cecille B. DeMille and Albert Payson Terhune), and Ramapo Valley Road (more or less paralleling the Ramapo River through Oakland) to [[Mahwah, New Jersey|Mahwah]] before crossing the New York state line on the [[Franklin Turnpike (New Jersey)|Franklin Turnpike]].\n\n[[Image:Bear Mtn Bridge.jpg|250px|thumb|View of the [[Bear Mountain Bridge]] from [[Bear Mountain (Hudson Highlands)|Bear Mountain]]]]\n\n===New York===\n<!-- This section is linked from [[Putnam County, New York]] -->\n{{main|U.S. Route 202 in New York}}\nUS&nbsp;202 is mostly designated east\u2013west in New York, owing to its greater coverage in those directions.\n\n[[Franklin Turnpike (New Jersey)|Franklin Turnpike]] becomes Orange Avenue in [[Suffern, New York|Suffern]], and US&nbsp;202 continues to a block-long [[wrong-way concurrency]] with [[New York State Route 59|NY 59]] before tailing off on Wayne Avenue and heading east toward [[Haverstraw, New York|Haverstraw]].  Most of this stretch is two-lane road.\n\nAt Haverstraw, US&nbsp;202 turns north along [[U.S. Route 9W|US&nbsp;9W]] to [[Bear Mountain (Hudson Highlands)|Bear Mountain]] and then crosses the [[Bear Mountain Bridge]], running concurrently with [[U.S. Route 6 in New York|US&nbsp;6]], the Grand Army Of The Republic Highway. The two wind around [[Anthony's Nose (Westchester)|Anthony's Nose]], briefly forming New York's only three-way concurrency of U.S. highways with [[U.S. Route 9 in New York|US&nbsp;9]] at [[Peekskill, New York|Peekskill]]. Afterwards, the two separate for several miles, with US&nbsp;202 taking the more southerly route through [[Somers, New York|Somers]]. The highways reunite at [[Brewster, New York|Brewster]] and become a four-lane road for their last few miles before the state line, taking in [[New York State Route 121|NY 121]] in the process.<ref>{{cite book| title=New York State Atlas and Gazetteer |author=DeLorme Mapping Company |publisher=DeLorme Mapping Company |year=1993 |isbn=0-89933-230-7 |pages=}}</ref>\n\n===Connecticut===\n{{main|U.S. Route 202 in Connecticut}}\nAt [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury]], US&nbsp;6 and 202 climb up onto [[Interstate 84 in Connecticut|I-84]], which had just been joined by the north\u2013south [[U.S. Route 7 in Connecticut|US&nbsp;7]], making a four-way concurrency.  US 7 and 202 split from I-84 and US&nbsp;6 at Exit 7. It is a two-lane road in southern [[Brookfield, Connecticut|Brookfield]] as it follows Federal Road. US 202 diverts from U.S.&nbsp;Route&nbsp;7 at the next exit to a parallel surface route. The US&nbsp;7 freeway continues for another {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} before it rejoins US&nbsp;202 at the Brookfield/New Milford town line. The now rejoined US&nbsp;7 and 202 approach [[New Milford, Connecticut|New Milford]] in bucolic [[Litchfield County, Connecticut|Litchfield County]], where they once again split.\n\nUS&nbsp;202 continues through [[Torrington, Connecticut|Torrington]] and on to [[Cherry Brook, Connecticut|Cherry Brook]], where it then runs concurrently with [[U.S. Route 44 in Connecticut|US&nbsp;44]] for several miles before turning northward at [[Avon, Connecticut|Avon]].  For the run to the state line, US&nbsp;202 runs concurrently with [[Connecticut Route 10|Route 10]].\n\n===Massachusetts===\nUnlike elsewhere in New England, US&nbsp;202 is posted as a north\u2013south highway in Massachusetts, as the highway runs mostly in those directions for its length through the state.\n\nUS&nbsp;202 and [[Massachusetts Route 10|Route 10]] enter the Bay State at the \"[[Congamond, Massachusetts|Congamond]] Notch\" in [[Southwick, Massachusetts|Southwick]], a southward jog in the state line that includes [[Congamond Lake]]. North of [[Westfield, Massachusetts|Westfield]], US&nbsp;202 turns eastward toward [[Holyoke, Massachusetts|Holyoke]], crosses the [[Joseph E. Muller Bridge]] and South Hadley Falls Interchange, traversing [[Massachusetts Route 116|MA 116]] and [[Massachusetts Route 33|MA 33]] toward [[Belchertown, Massachusetts|Belchertown]].  After crossing [[Massachusetts Route 9|MA 9]], it then heads north along the west side of the [[Quabbin Reservoir]] through [[New Salem, Massachusetts|New Salem]] toward [[Athol, Massachusetts|Athol]].  This section of US&nbsp;202 has been dubbed the [[Daniel Shays]] Highway, named for a Revolutionary War veteran who [[Shays' Rebellion|led an insurrection]] against the state government of Massachusetts. US&nbsp;202 meets [[Massachusetts Route 2]] at [[Orange, Massachusetts|Orange]], and runs along the [[two-lane freeway]] to [[Phillipston, Massachusetts|Phillipston]].  There, it diverges to the north again as a two-lane road.\n\nIn Massachusetts, US&nbsp;202 passes through the municipalities of [[Southwick, MA|Southwick]], [[Westfield, MA|Westfield]], [[Holyoke, MA|Holyoke]], [[South Hadley, MA|South Hadley]], [[Granby, MA|Granby]], [[Belchertown, MA|Belchertown]], [[Pelham, MA|Pelham]], [[Shutesbury, MA|Shutesbury]], [[New Salem, MA|New Salem]], [[Orange, MA|Orange]], [[Athol, MA|Athol]], [[Phillipston, MA|Phillipston]], [[Templeton, MA|Templeton]], and [[Winchendon, MA|Winchendon]].\n\nThe stretch of highway through Belchertown, Pelham, Shutesbury, and New Salem opened in 1935 to coincide with the completion and opening of the Quabbin Reservoir. The roadway reaches its closest point to the reservoir itself at the crossing of the Swift River, at the Shutesbury/New Salem town line. Access to the west side of the Quabbin Reservation is made through multiple gates in the three towns. There is no public access, however, to the Prescott Peninsula.\n\n===New Hampshire=== \n[[File:Centerline Rumble Strip.jpg|thumb|Section of US 202 in Henniker, NH]]\nUS&nbsp;202 is posted as an east\u2013west highway in New Hampshire. It remains a two-lane highway for most of its length in the Granite State.\n\nIt heads north, through [[Rindge, New Hampshire|Rindge]], [[Jaffrey, New Hampshire|Jaffrey]], and [[Peterborough, New Hampshire|Peterborough]], to [[Hillsborough, New Hampshire|Hillsborough]], where it turns eastward along a concurrency with [[New Hampshire Route 9]]. The span of the road between Hillsborough and [[Hopkinton, New Hampshire|Hopkinton]], which passes through [[Henniker, New Hampshire|Henniker]], is among the most deadly sections of roadway in the state.<ref>[http://www.cmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050605/REPOSITORY/506050432/1031 \"Crash takes two lives\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927214230/http://www.cmonitor.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20050605%2FREPOSITORY%2F506050432%2F1031 |date=September 27, 2007 }}. ''[[Concord Monitor]]''. June 2005. Accessed July 10, 2008.</ref> At [[Concord, New Hampshire]], the state capital, US&nbsp;202 heads north and picks up a concurrency with [[U.S. Route 3|US&nbsp;3]] for a short time, and then turns eastward again along [[Interstate 393]], a freeway spur that also carries [[U.S. Route 4|US&nbsp;4]].  The freeway ends short of [[Chichester, New Hampshire|Chichester]], and NH 9 rejoins the two-lane concurrency along with US&nbsp;4 and 202.\n\nAt [[Northwood, New Hampshire|Northwood]], US&nbsp;202 and NH 9 leave US&nbsp;4.  NH 9 splits off a few miles later, leaving US&nbsp;202 to continue alone toward [[Rochester, New Hampshire|Rochester]], where the road jumps up onto the [[Spaulding Turnpike]] ([[New Hampshire Route 16|NH 16]]) for a short, non-tolled distance.  US&nbsp;202 leaves the turnpike two miles (3&nbsp;km) before the state line at [[East Rochester, New Hampshire|East Rochester]].\n\n===Maine===\n[[Image:NewEnglandConnectingFarm.png|thumb|[[Connected farm]] in [[Windham, Maine]], typical of older residences adjacent to Route 202 through rural [[New England]].]]\n\nUS&nbsp;202 is posted as an east\u2013west highway in Maine.\n\nThe highway enters the state by crossing the [[Salmon Falls River]] at [[Lebanon, Maine|South Lebanon]] and bridges the [[Mousam River]] in [[Sanford, Maine|Sanford]]. The highway then passes through [[Alfred, Maine|Alfred]], [[Waterboro, Maine|Waterboro]] and [[Hollis, Maine|Hollis]] before crossing the [[Saco River]] at [[Buxton, Maine|Salmon Falls]]. The highway passes through [[Gorham, Maine|Gorham]] and crosses the [[Presumpscot River]] into [[South Windham, Maine|South Windham]]. There is a rotary with [[U.S. Route 302]] at [[Windham, Maine|Foster's Corner]] and an interchange with [[Interstate 95 in Maine|I-95]] at [[Gray, Maine|Gray]]. The highway parallels I-95 through [[New Gloucester, Maine|New Gloucester]] to [[Auburn, Maine|Auburn]] and crosses the [[Androscoggin River]] into [[Lewiston, Maine|Lewiston]], passing near the campus of [[Bates College]].<ref name=\"maine\">{{cite book| title=The Maine Atlas and Gazetteer |author=DeLorme Mapping Company |publisher=DeLorme Mapping Company |year=1988 |isbn=0-89933-035-5 |pages=}}</ref> A very short stretch through the latter two cities is four-lane highway, but most of its length in the Pine Tree State consists of two-lane road. Its final miles west of [[Hampden, Maine|Hampden]], including the short overlay on I-395, and concurrency with US&nbsp;1A also include four-laned segments.\n\nThe highway passes through [[Greene, Maine|Greene]], [[Monmouth, Maine|Monmouth]], and [[Winthrop, Maine|Winthrop]] concurrently with [[State Route 11 (Maine)|Maine Route 11]] and [[State Route 100 (Maine)|Maine Route 100]], and becomes concurrent with [[State Route 17 (Maine)|State Route 17]] at [[Manchester, Maine|Manchester]]. US&nbsp;202 runs concurrently with [[U.S. Route 201]] as it crosses the [[Kennebec River]] at [[Augusta, Maine|Augusta]], and shortly thereafter it picks up [[State Route 3 (Maine)|State Route 3]] and [[State Route 9 (Maine)|State Route 9]].  Maine 3 splits off at [[South China, Maine|South China]], but Maine 9 stays with US&nbsp;202 through [[Albion, Maine|Albion]], [[Unity, Maine|Unity]], [[Troy, Maine|Troy]], [[Dixmont, Maine|Dixmont]], [[Newburgh, Maine|Newburgh]], and [[Hampden, Maine|Hampden]] almost all the way to its terminus in [[Bangor, Maine|Bangor]].<ref name=\"maine\"/> When Maine 9 turns right onto Summer Street in Bangor with US&nbsp;1A, US&nbsp;202 runs four more blocks to its eastern (or northern) terminus at the US&nbsp;2 intersection at the corner of Hammond, Main, Central and State Streets.\n\n==History==\n{{infobox road small\n|country=USA\n|type=US 1926\n|route=122\n|location=[[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington, DE]]\u2013[[Haverstraw, New York|Haverstraw, NY]]\n|length_mi=\n|length_ref=\n|length_round=\n|formed=1926\n|deleted=1934\n}}\n'''U.S.&nbsp;Route&nbsp;122''' was created in 1926, connecting [[US 22 (NJ)|US&nbsp;22]] at [[Whitehouse Station, New Jersey]], with [[Wilmington, Delaware]]. It was extended to [[Haverstraw, New York]] in 1931 and became part of US 202 in 1934.\n\nUS 202 was approved by AASHO in June 1934; the route approved was {{convert|671|mi}}, from Bangor, Maine, to [[State Road, Delaware]], south of Wilmington. In 1964, AASHO approved a request by Delaware to eliminate the portion of US 202 between its intersection with I-295 in [[Farnhurst, Delaware|Farnhurst]] and State Road; that stretch was carrying US 13/40/301. US 202 was later shortened so that it ended at I-95 just north of Wilmington.  Then in 1984, the route numbering committee approved extending US 202 from there to its intersection with US 13/US 40 in [[Basin Corner, Delaware|Basin Corner]], near [[New Castle, Delaware|New Castle]]. This intersection is US 202's current terminus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/infrastructure/us202.cfm|title=U.S. 202 - Maine to Delaware - General Highway History - Highway History - Federal Highway Administration|website=www.fhwa.dot.gov|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUS 202's path passes near the sites of various important [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] battles in Delaware and Pennsylvania, such as [[Cooch's Bridge]], near Newark, Delaware; [[Brandywine Battlefield|Brandywine]], near Philadelphia; and [[Valley Forge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.revolutionaryday.com/usroute202/tour.htm|title=Introduction, US Route 202, Revolutionary War, History-based Travel, Road Trip Driving Tour of the American Revolution|website=www.revolutionaryday.com|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref> In New Hampshire, US 202 passes by a historical marker in [[Antrim, New Hampshire|Antrim]] commemorating the last surviving soldier of the Revolutionary War.<ref>https://www.nh.gov/nhdhr/markers/documents/markers_bynumber.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unionleader.com/nh/travel/historical_markers/roadside-history-joel-mcgregor-last-surviving-soldier-of-the-revolution/article_bcb31e51-da51-5eed-9de6-d14b725acc46.html|title=Roadside History: Joel McGregor, Last Surviving Soldier of the Revolution|date=March 31, 2017|website=UnionLeader.com|language=en|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Pennsylvania in the early 1960s, a four-lane [[Limited-access road|expressway]], the Piedmont Expressway, was proposed that would follow the US&nbsp;202 corridor. The expressway was to be {{convert|59|mi}} long, and would cost approximately $146 million. It was to serve as an outer [[beltway]] around the Philadelphia area. The project was ultimately cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pahighways.com/us/US202.html |title=Pennsylvania Highways:\u00a0US 202 |website=www.pahighways.com |access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref> In its place, the Route 202 Parkway Trail was built. The trail is {{convert|9|mi|0}} in length.<ref>https://circuittrails.org/sites/default/files/08_Route202.pdf</ref> The trail is ultimately expected to connect to the [[East Coast Greenway]] via the Neshaminy Creek Trail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://circuittrails.org/find-trails/neshaminy-creek-greenway-extension|title=Neshaminy Creek Greenway Extension|date=June 8, 2016|website=Circuit|language=en|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nConstruction began in November 2008 on a parkway project between [[Pennsylvania Route 63]] in Lower Gwynedd and the existing cloverleaf interchange at the US&nbsp;202 Bypass and PA 611 near Doylestown.  This parkway was planned to consist of a four-lane stretch between Route 63 and [[Pennsylvania Route 463]] and a two-lane parkway the rest of the way that bypasses the [[Borough (Pennsylvania)|borough]]s of [[Chalfont, Pennsylvania|Chalfont]] and [[New Britain, Pennsylvania|New Britain]]. The parkway opened on December 3, 2012.<ref name=\"intell12312\"/>\n\nUS 202 originally ended at its junction with US 2/US 1A in Bangor, Maine. In the late 1980s, however, the section of US 202 between I-395 and US 2 was removed from US 202's official routing. Officially, US 202 ends at I-395's exit 3. However, signs designating US 202's termination at US 2 in downtown Bangor, at the corner of Main Street and Hammond Street, still stand today. That intersection is still seen as US 202's end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usends.com/202.html|title=End of US highway 202|website=US Ends.com|language=en|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.floodgap.com/roadgap/me/r?202|title=US Highway 202 (Maine)|date=2010|website=RoadsAroundME|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n;Delaware\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|13|US|40}} in [[Wilmington Manor, Delaware|Wilmington Manor]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|295|dab1=Delaware\u2013New Jersey}} in [[Newport, Delaware|Newport]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|95}} with a concurrency from [[Newport, Delaware|Newport]] to [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|495|dab1=Delaware}} in [[Newport, Delaware|Newport]]\n\n;Pennsylvania\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|1|US|322}} in [[Chadds Ford Township, Pennsylvania|Chadds Ford Township]], with a concurrency with US 322 from Chadds Ford Township to [[West Goshen Township, Pennsylvania|West Goshen Township]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|30}} in [[East Whiteland Township, Pennsylvania|East Whiteland Township]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|422}} in [[Tredyffrin Township, Pennsylvania|Tredyffrin Township]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|76|I|276|dab1=Ohio\u2013New Jersey}} in [[Upper Merion Township, Pennsylvania|Upper Merion Township]]\n\n;New Jersey\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|206}} with a concurrency from the [[Raritan, New Jersey|Raritan]]\u2013[[Bridgewater Township, New Jersey|Bridgewater Township]] line to [[Bedminster Township, New Jersey|Bedminster Township]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|22}} in [[Bridgewater Township, New Jersey|Bridgewater Township]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|287}} in [[Bridgewater Township, New Jersey|Bridgewater Township]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|287}} in [[Bedminster Township, New Jersey|Bedminster Township]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|80}} in [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|46}} in [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|287}} in [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|287}} in [[Boonton, New Jersey|Boonton]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|287}} in [[Montville, New Jersey|Montville]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|287}} in [[Oakland, New Jersey|Oakland]]\n\n;New York\n: {{jct|state=NY|US|9W}} with a concurrency from the [[Haverstraw (village), New York|Village of Haverstraw]] to [[Highlands, New York|Highlands]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|6}} with a concurrency from [[Highlands, New York|Highlands]] to [[Peekskill, New York|Peekskill]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|9}} with a concurrency from [[Cortlandt, New York|Cortlandt]] to [[Peekskill, New York|Peekskill]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|6}} with a concurrency from [[Brewster, New York|Brewster]] to the [[Connecticut]] state line in [[Southeast, New York|Southeast]]\n\n;Connecticut\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|6}} with a concurrency from the [[New York (state)|New York]] state line in [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury]] through the city\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|84|dab1=Pennsylvania\u2013Massachusetts}} with a concurrency through [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|7}} with a concurrency from [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury]] to [[New Milford, Connecticut|New Milford]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|44}} with a concurrency from [[Canton, Connecticut|Canton]] to [[Avon, Connecticut|Avon]]\n\n;Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Maine\n{{jcttop|exit|state_col=state|length_ref=<ref name=\"NHDOT Roads\">{{cite web|url=http://www.granit.unh.edu/data/search?dset=roads_dot|title=NH Public Roads|author=Bureau of Planning & Community Assistance|date=February 20, 2015|website=|publisher=[[New Hampshire Department of Transportation]]|place=Concord, New Hampshire|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NH Town Maps\">{{cite web|url=ftp://dot%2Ecity:streetmap@nhftp.admin.state.nh.us/2015_FULL_SIZE_PDFS/|title=Nodal Reference 2015, State of New Hampshire|author=Bureau of Planning & Community Assistance|date=April 3, 2015|website=|publisher=[[New Hampshire Department of Transportation]]|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=Internet